<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Witnesses Record Revenue Increase in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government's
revenue hit a record high to reach 77.2 billion shillings (about
96.5 million U.S. dollars) in May due to a boost in the collection
of income tax, customs duty and value added tax.
</P>
<P>
This represented an increase of 23.2 billion shillings (about
29 million dollars) compared to the revenue collected in the
previous month, the Bank of Tanzania said in its latest monthly
economic review.
</P>
<P>
According to the central bank, government expenditure in May
amounted to 76.5 billion shillings (about 95.6 million dollars), a
figure which is 12.9 billion shillings (about 16.1 million dollars)
higher than that for April.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the annual headline inflation rate remained stable
at a minimal 6 percent throughout April and May, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Measured on a month-to-month basis, the overall inflation went
down by 0.8 percentage point in May.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank cautioned that the declining trend in
the overall inflation may be subdued by food shortages in several
regions of the country, though the trend is expected to continue
in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, the bank's governor Daudi Ballali expressed
his optimism about Tanzania's economy and outlined several
conditions to be fulfilled within the next 18 months before the
country qualifies fully for debt relief conditions given by the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to the governor, the main condition is to maintain
macro-economic stability, particularly having sustainable economic
growth and low inflation levels.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's economic record in the last five years is clearly
impressive. The economy has been growing at about 4.8 percent,
well above the 2.8 percent population growth, while the annual
inflation was kept at 6.6 percent as of May.
</P>
<P>
There are clear signs that economic growth in the eastern
African country will continue to maintain the upward trend,
following interest being shown by foreign investors in various
sectors of the economy, including industry, mining, agriculture
and tourism, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
