<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers' Welfare Committee in EPZs Endorsed by Bangladeshi PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Prime Minister's office has
finally endorsed the Workers' Welfare Committee as outlined by
Bangladesh Export Processing Zones Authority (BEPZA), Commerce
Minister Abdul Jalil said at an inter-ministerial meeting
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The commerce minister said the Prime Minister's office endorsed
the framework of the committee with some changes and decided that
the labor groups in Export Processing Zones (EPZs) would select
their representatives in the welfare committee.
</P>
<P>
A committee headed by the Board of Investment (BOI) Executive
Chairman on July 4 formulated the framework of Workers' Welfare
Committee and neutral Labor Relations Tribunal to ensure workers'
rights in the EPZs.
</P>
<P>
The BEPZA first outlined the formula to avoid direct trade
unionism in the EPZs as all the investors excepting those from the
United States opposed the U.S. move for allowing trade union
activities in the EPZs.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government primarily opposed the U.S. idea but
finally considered some sort of labor union type under tremendous
pressure which included a threat of canceling Generalized System
of Preference facilities on Bangladesh exports to the U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has long been pressing Bangladesh
government to allow trade union activities in the exclusive
economic zones under the pressure of the American Federation of
Labor and Congress for Industrial Organization.
</P>
<P>
A Bangladeshi delegation, led by Commerce Minister Abdul Jalil,
is likely to go to Washington next month to explain Bangladesh's
position and its alternative measures for ensuring EPZ workers'
rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
