<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Start Peacekeeping Operation in Ethio-Eritrean Border Region: Major General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations, together
with the Organization of African Unity (OAU), will deploy
peacekeeping forces along the Ethiopia-Eritrean border as soon as
possible in a bid to keep the momentum of peaceful settlement of
the border dispute between the two countries, a senior U.N.-
designated military officer said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I have an impression that both Ethiopia and Eritrea have the
will for peace, the two countries want to have the peacekeeping
forces deployed at their border region as soon as possible," said
Major General Timothy Ford of the U.N. Reconnaissance Mission.
</P>
<P>
He said that pending the deployment of peacekeeping forces,
the United Nations will deploy liaison officers in the capitals of
both countries within a few days.
</P>
<P>
It is anticipated that there will be five to six U.N. liaison
officers and about three OAU officials, Ford said, noting that "
this will be the first U.N. presence in this area."
</P>
<P>
When asked about the structure of the peacekeeping troops, the
general said that there will be military observers supported by
peacekeeping troops including aviation unit, demining unit,
engineering unit and logistic unit.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question where the U.N. peacekeeping troops
will be deployed, Ford said that the troops will be deployed in a
temporary security zone that is yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
Under the cessation of hostility agreement signed by Ethiopia
and Eritrea in Algiers on June 18, the Ethiopian troops will not
withdraw from their position which is about 25 kilometers inside
Eritrea until the deployment of U.N. peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
According to Ford, the number of countries contributing
peacekeeping troops has not been decided either, but he confirmed
that the neighboring countries of Ethiopia and Eritrea will not be
involved.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the U.N. peacekeeping forces will be
deployed as quickly as possible. It is important to complete the
deployment before the end of rainy season, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the demining along the Ethio-Eritrean border, the
major general said that all mines in the region must be cleared so
as to pave way for the deployment of the peacekeeping troops and
to avoid deaths and injuries of people.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in addition to international effort, it is
also the responsibility of the governments of Ethiopia and Eritrea
to carry on with the demining activity.
</P>
<P>
Ford and his entourage arrived here Tuesday after a four-day
visit to Eritrea where they visited key sites along the frontlines
and held discussions with Eritrean officials on the implementation
of the cease-fire agreement as well as on the U.N. peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Ford had similar discussions with Ethiopian
military authorities over the establishment of a temporary
security zone along the Ethio-Eritrean border region, a military
coordination commission, the main tasks and composition of a U.N.
peacekeeping operation and demining.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. reconnaissance team headed by Ford has also conferred
with the diplomatic community based in Addis Ababa on the
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
Ford is due to make a field visit to the northern front of
Ethiopia, before departing for New York next Tuesday to prepare
and submit his findings and recommendations to U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan concerning the deployment of a U.N.
peacekeeping force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
