<HEADLINE> OAU Leaders Proclaim May 25 Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity (
OAU) leaders Wednesday declared May 25 as a work-free day
throughout the continent to raise awareness of integration.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the 36th annual summit of the OAU from
July 10 to 12 in the Togolese capital Lome, where the leaders
signed a draft treaty on the establishment of the African Union,
signaling a milestone in the process of political and economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
On the holiday, appropriate activities will be organized to
bring African peoples closer together, reaffirm their faith in the
integration and popularize the ideals of union in the continent.
</P>
<P>
May 25 was set as African Liberation Day when 32 independent
African states adopted the Charter of the OAU in 1963 in Addis
Ababa, Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Calls for Help to Curb AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 12 (Xinhua) -- African leaders appealed here on
Wednesday to the international community to join Africa in the
fight against HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration on HIV/AIDS in Africa issued at the end of a
three-day annual summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
the leaders were gravely concerned about the rapid spread of HIV
infection in Africa and the millions of deaths caused by AIDS
throughout the continent in spite of the serious efforts to combat
this scourge.
</P>
<P>
The leaders committed themselves to take personal
responsibility and provide leadership for the fight against the
scourge of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
They resolved to keep the question of HIV/AIDS high on national
agenda for health, social, cultural and economic activities and to
make it a development issue.
</P>
<P>
They also pledged to develop and enact national strategies to
deal with HIV/AIDS as a priority within national development plans.
</P>
<P>
Currently 34.3 million people are infected with HIV that causes
AIDS, 24.5 million of them being in sub-Saharan Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
