<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Parliament Condemns Arrest of Turkish Cypriot Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus House of Representatives
President Spyros Kyprianou on Thursday protested against the arrest
of Turkish Cypriot journalists by the breakaway Turkish Cypriot
regime of the island.
</P>
<P>
Kyprianou made the protest in a letter to European Parliament
President Nicole Fontaine, President of the Parliamentary Assembly
of the Council of Europe Lord Russell Johnston and Secretary
General of the International Federation of Journalists Aidan White.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia. In 1983 the Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a
breakaway state in northern Cyprus which is only recognized by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
According to Greek Cypriot media, the chief editor and three
journalists of the Turkish Cypriot newspaper Avrupa and two other
persons in the Turkish Cypriot area were arrested last week on
charges of spying against the Turkish Cypriot regime and Turkish
troops, which controls northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Kyprianou said in the letter that the Cyprus parliament "
condemns this abhorrent act" aimed at muzzling voices which could
be heard in favor of rapprochement between Greek and Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Kyprianou urged the international community, all
parliamentarians and journalists in particular, to intervene in an
effective manner for the immediate release of the arrested.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sarah de Jung, an official of the International
Federation of Journalists, will arrive here Friday to investigate
the
case.
</P>
<P>
Reports said de Jung will visit Sener Levent and the other
journalists detained, as well as the Avrupa's offices.
</P>
<P>
She will also seek a meeting with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash and Turkish Cypriot party leaders to demand immediate
release of the journalists and an end to the persecution of the
newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
