<HEADLINE> Xinhua Middle East News Summary at 2000 GMT, Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Culture Minister Istemihan Talay has promised
to return two smuggled Picasso oil paintings to their real owners,
reported Turkish Daily News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two paintings "La Fermiere" and "Dora Maar" were seized by
police in Izmir, southwest of Turkey, in two separate operations
while smugglers were trying to sell them, by chance, to undercover
police last month. (Turkey-Picasso-Paintings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli police arrested six Palestinians after an
exchange of fire in east Jerusalem on Thursday, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The policemen, who were undercover on a mission in the Ras al-
Amud neighborhood near the Old City in east Jerusalem, were
attacked Thursday morning by a group of armed men from a house.
There was an exchange of fire and more police were called in.
</P>
<P>
Police reinforcements surrounded the building and the six men
gave themselves in. (Israel-Criminal Incident)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Mesut Yilmaz, leader of Turkey's junior ruling partner
Motherland Party (ANAP), was appointed on Thursday as state
minister and deputy prime minister for the European Union affairs
while Cumhur Ersumer was dismissed from his post as deputy prime
minister but retained the post of state minister for energy.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet was partially reshuffled at the request of Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit. It was accepted by Turkish President Ahmet
Necdet Sezer and was issued in the Official Gazette on the same
day. (Turkey-Coalition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A passenger plane of Egypt's national carrier flew to
Libya on Thursday, resuming regular flights between the two
countries after a hiatus of eight years due to international
sanctions imposed on Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The EgyptAir plane carried 71 passengers and 62 civil aviation
officials, who will discuss some remaining technical issues with
their Libyan counterparts, the state-run Middle East News Agency
reported. (Egypt-Libya-Flight Resumption)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates' Minister of Petroleum and
Mineral Resources Obeid bin Saif Al Nassiri said on Thursday that
his country has no intention of increasing its oil output
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
He added that any decision on such an increase will come within
the framework of the decision of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), of which the UAE is a member. (UAE-
Venezuela-Oil) 
</P>
</TEXT>
