<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Vows to Improve Economic Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia is trying to create
conditions favoring expansion of industry and the entire economy
rather than winning short-term popular support, President Vladimir
Putin said in an interview to be published in the Friday edition
of the Izvestia newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The state has been honoring all its social commitments, making
use of the favorable situation on the world markets, but will not
expand its social programs without proper consideration, the
Interfax news agency quoted Putin as saying in the interview.
</P>
<P>
"The state has been working to meet the targets of budget macro-
indexes. Now, for the first time in the years of reform, budget
revenue exceeds expenditures," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the state has acted more vigorously "in the
spheres related to business such as taxation and law enforcement
in the economy."
</P>
<P>
"You can see that we act cautiously but are moving forward,"
Putin said.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the measures have met with strong resistance,
but the state does not "resort to unconstitutional steps."
</P>
<P>
"Whenever it is in the scope of the executive branch we pass a
presidential decree or a Cabinet ordinance, but some issues cannot
be resolved in the framework of existing law, and then we go to
the Duma," the lower house of parliament, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Those who offer resistance will do their utmost to discredit
our steps," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
He accused some business people of "trying to settle accounts
by using state agencies, law enforcement agencies."
</P>
<P>
"This practice has to end," the president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
