<HEADLINE> U.S. Attorney Promises to Review Internet "wiretapping" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno promised Thursday to review the e-mail monitoring system used
by the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) so that privacy can
be safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
"When we develop new technology, when we apply the Constitution,
I want to make sure that we apply it in a consistent and balanced
way," Reno said at her weekly news briefing.
</P>
<P>
"I'm taking a look at it now," she said, "if additional
regulations are needed, we will pursue those."
</P>
<P>
She said that she is looking into FBI's new high-tech "
Carnivore" system to ensure that privacy safeguards and the needs
of federal law enforcement officials are met.
</P>
<P>
The "Carnivore" system can scan all incoming and outgoing e-
mails for messages associated with the target of a criminal probe.
</P>
<P>
"It can be a wonderful tool and I don't want it to be a tool
that is, in any way, a cause of concern for privacy interests,"
Reno said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. civil rights group have complained that the system
breaches the Internet provider's rights and the rights of all its
customers by reading e-mails and their addresses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
