<HEADLINE> Greece Dismisses Denktash's Criticism Over Geneva Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 ATHENS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Greece Thursday dismissed the
charges made by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash over Greece's
"interference" in the Geneva proximity talks, saying that Denktash
must realize that he was not the judge but the one who was being
judged.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas urged Denktash to comply with the framework of the
U.N. resolutions and contribute to a solution to the Cyprus issue,
which he was not doing but, on the contrary, he was undermining.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
To reunite the divided island, The Greek Cypriot side-led by
President Glafcos Clerides and the Turkish Cypriot side-led by
Denktash have held two rounds of the U.N.-sponsored indirect talks
in Geneva and New York, and the third round of such talks ended in
Geneva Wednesday with no sign of progress.
</P>
<P>
Greek ministers said earlier this week that Denktash's
positions was unacceptable as it envisaged the continuing division
of the island, and Denktash complained that Athens was trying to "
kill the talks through unacceptable interference."
</P>
<P>
Greece, who signed a joint defense pact with Nicosia, and
Clerides has insisted that the island must be reunited in a
federation formula in line with the U.N. resolutions while the
Turkey and Denktash demand that a confederation formed by two
sovereign states be set up on the eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
</TEXT>
