<HEADLINE> Putin: Authorities Must Be Strong, Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, Putin said, the authorities must be open at the same
time, because "if the authorities remain in place thanks only to
restrictions and prohibitions... the value of such authorities is
zero."
</P>
<P>
"The authorities cannot be truly effective or strong unless
they are open, predictable and use their tools to protect the
dignity of the people, their liberties and right to choose," the
Interfax news agency quoted the Putin as saying in the interview.
</P>
<P>
"It is a deeply entrenched Russian habit to curse the
authorities, to fear them and not expect anything good to come
from them," Putin said. He attributed it to what he described as
the country's horrible history and the "continuous changing of the
rules of the road, the instability of property rules (and)
inconsistent legislation."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, "while the state was loosening the reins on
the economy, tax dodging and other abuses have assumed a massive
scale, so numerous businessmen risk strained relations with the
law. They have every reason to be nervous," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
"It would hardly be fair to shift the blame onto individuals
and make believe that the state is not responsible for the
situation. This is the reason why we have taken steps designed to
improve the entrepreneurial climate in the country," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Bills concerning taxes and deductions to extra-budgetary funds
have already been sent to the State Duma, the lower house of
parliament, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Once these measures are approved, a new stage of conscientious
mutual responsibility and mutual commitments between the
authorities and the business community will settle in, he said.
</P>
