<HEADLINE> UAE Says No Intention to Unilaterally Raise Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates'
Minister of Petroleum and Mineral Resources Obeid bin Saif Al
Nassiri said on Thursday that his country has no intention of
increasing its oil output unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
He added that any decision on such an increase will come within
the framework of the decision of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), of which the UAE is a member.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after a closed-door meeting with visiting
Venezuelan Energy and Mines Minister and OPEC president Ali
Rodriguez Araque, who was on a lightning visit to the UAE,
according to the official WAM news agency.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued at the end of the meeting, the
ministers emphasized their countries' determination to maintain
stability of the oil market and to cooperate with other OPEC
members and non-OPEC oil producing countries in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Both agreed that fluctuations on world oil market are not in the
interest of either the producers or the consumers in the long run.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Ali Rodriguez said the two sides had
exchanged ideas on the current oil market and had agreed on all
points of their discussions. He dismissed the necessity of an OPEC
emergency meeting to assess the oil market situation.
</P>
<P>
He added that he also discussed with his UAE counterpart a
number of other issues including the OPEC summit scheduled in the
Venezuelan capital of Caracas in September and the upcoming visit
of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez to the UAE on August 9.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez was on a tour of the region which had already taken
him to Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, during which he discussed with
officials of the two countries the situation in oil market, which
has seen prices hovering around 30 U.S. dollars per barrel.
</P>
</TEXT>
