<HEADLINE> Lebanon Approves Draft on E-signatures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese government approved a draft
on Wednesday to legalize electronic and digital signatures as well
as electronic documents, Daily Star newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The move is supposed to galvanize e-commerce and propel Lebanon
into the Internet age, where business often flounders in a sea of
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is the first Arab country to pass such a legislation and
among a few of European nations as well as the United States, which
are similarly equipped such legislation.
</P>
<P>
Economy Minister Nasser Saidi said the law is "a revolution." He
showed his confidence that the law would be instrumental in
generating trade to fight the current recession.
</P>
<P>
"This law will buttressed the program for a new economy and the
new law allows a major jump in the legal basis for all
transactions," he said. He vowed that Lebanon is entering the
information age and the software that gives a proper legal
framework is "critical."
</P>
<P>
He also said the new law, which took four or five months to
draft, will introduce a degree of flexibility which would allow for
change.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that he has always been a strong believer
in electronic government and he hope that the law would create a
better relationship between the public and various government
ministries.
</P>
<P>
"It is a real administrative reform that will cut through much
of the bureaucracy that traditionally strangles the country", he
said, hoping "the computer will be the direct link between the
citizen and the ministry." 
</P>
</TEXT>
