<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jordanian Cabinet Wins Overwhelming Support From Lower House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's new government headed by
Prime Minister Ali Abu Ragheb on Thursday won a vote of confidence
in the lower house of the National Assembly (parliament).
</P>
<P>
The new government won 74 favorable votes in the 80-seat House
of Representatives as against only six blackballs, believed to be
the most overwhelming victory in the kingdom's history.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb had headed the Economic and Financial Committee of the
House before he was appointed prime minister in mid-June by King
Abdullah Bin Hussein, who has the constitutional rights of sacking,
appointing governments or dissolving the parliament.
</P>
<P>
A new prime minister is subject to a vote of confidence in the
House four weeks after the appointment by the monarch.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's vote came after three days of debate in the House
during which 75 deputies took the podium to call on the government
to improve services, fight corruption, nepotism, bloated
bureaucracy, poverty and soaring unemployment.
</P>
<P>
On international issues, many deputies asked the government to
help realize the right to return of the Palestinian refugees living
in the kingdom and their adequate compensation; and many others
called on the government to bolster relations with Arab countries,
notably with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In his reply to deputies during the debate, Ragheb reiterated
that the government wants a role in any Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations on the refugee issue to ensure the right to return or
compensation of the 1.5 million Palestinians refugees seeking
shelter in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Most of the refugees here have been granted Jordanian
citizenship, but the government supports their rights to choose
between returning to their homeland or staying in the kingdom while
asking for compensation from parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
On relations with Iraq, Ragheb affirmed that Jordan sought an
end to the United Nations sanctions imposed on Iraq, the main
supplier of oil of Jordan, since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also pledged to implement sweeping reforms,
including broader freedom for the press and political parties and
drafting a modern election law.
</P>
<P>
On economy, he said the situation was not easy and the
government was faced with a big challenge, but he projected a 3-
percent economic growth for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a royal decree to appoint Ragheb prime minister, King
Abdullah asked the government to make it a top priority to develop
national economy and improve the living standards of the people.
</P>
<P>
One third of the Jordanians are living below the poverty line --
with a monthly income of less than 80 dinars (112 U.S. dollars) --
and the unemployment rate stands at over 14 percent by official
statistics while independent estimates put it at 27 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Detention of Egyptian-American Professor in Egypt Prolonged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian higher state security
prosecution on Thursday renewed detention for another 15 days of
Saad Eddin Ibrahim, an Egyptian-American sociology professor at the

American University in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Maher Abdel Wahed approved the decision taken
by the security prosecution in the presence of Ibrahim who was
charged with undermining Egypt's social stability, the country's
official Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim, also director of the Ibn Khaldoun Center for
Development Studies, was accused of taking money from foreign
sources to draft
reports on the internal situation in Egypt and produce a film
tarnishing the country's reputation. He was also charged with
fomenting internal problems that could threaten Egypt's stability.
</P>
<P>
Nadia Mohamed Abul Nour, an accountant of the center, will also
be detained for 15 more days pending investigations, the news
agency said. Ibrahim and Nour were arrested on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prosecution ordered on Wednesday the detention of
four other people for 15 days, bringing the total number held in
the case to 13.
</P>
<P>
The investigators said the four -- one from the Ibn Khaldoun
Center and the three others from the Women Voters' Support Center,
affiliated to Ibrahim's center -- received bribes from Ibrahim to
forge voting cards.
</P>
<P>
Stacks of voting cards have been seized from Ibrahim's center,
and investigators have accused him of paying people for forging the
cards and registering names of fictitious voters on them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
