have recently allocated 76 million birr (about 9.4 million U.S.
dollars) in a bid to protect and study various relics of ancient
society, the Ethiopian Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Renovation and research works on historical sites in Axum and
Lalibela as well as in the monasteries in Gondar have been started
at the cost of 2.6 million birr (about 310,000 U.S. dollars)
allocated by the Ministry of Information and Culture.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has also conducted maintenance work on Emperor
Fasil Castle and Emperor Bakafa's Palace. Preparations are under
way to the rock-hewn churches of Lalibela with an outlay of 40
million birr (nearly 5 million U.S. dollars) secured from the
European Union in aid.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the ministry has also finalized preliminary
preparations to construct relics preservation laboratory in Addis
Ababa at the cost of 34 million birr (about 4.2 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Axum, situated in far north of Ethiopia, is the birth place of
Ethiopia's civilization and is the first ancient holy city in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Famous for its monolithic churches, Lalibela, some 400
kilometers north of Addis Ababa, is one of the greatest tourist
attraction in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Gondar, about 500 kilometers north of the capital, was the
capital of Ethiopia from 1636 to 1864. Emperor Fasil Castle in the
city represents one of the world's mysteries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
