<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists at AIDS Conference on Significance of "Durban Declaration" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A panel of scientists from
Africa, Asia, Europe, North and Latin America unanimously agreed
on Thursday that the controversial so-called "Durban Declaration"
had paved the way for future scientific debate on HIV within
orthodox parameters.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Hoosen Coovadia, chairman of the 13th International AIDS
Conference, said the document had been a watershed in the debate
that raged recently in South Africa regarding the link between HIV
and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"The importance of this document cannot be underestimated. To
me it stands in belief of scientific principles," he said.
</P>
<P>
Durban Declaration, which a total of 5,000 scientists across
the world signed before the conference, categorically refuted the
assertion by dissidents that the HIV might not cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Coovadia, also a member of South African President Thabo Mbeki
's AIDS panel, said the Durban Declaration was never meant to be
an attack on the president.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he believed the dissidents in the panel never
took the HIV debate any further in any constructive way.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Chewe Luo from Zambia said the future of the declaration
should not hinge on the Mbeki angle, adding that HIV was killing
people and to ask whether HIV caused AIDS was futile.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, Botswana and Zambia, which had high infection
levels because of inaction, could be an warning for other
countries where infection levels were not yet so rampant, Luo said.
</P>
<P>
American scientist Dr. Charles Van Der Horst, who was involved
in the initial coordination of the draft of the Durban Declaration
a month ago, said he sent electronic messages to eminent
scientists around the world, petitioning the cause.
</P>
<P>
He received an overwhelming response, including from 12 Nobel
Prize Laureates.
</P>
<P>
"The scientific evidence that HIV causes AIDS is unambiguous.
The unprecedented document has been backed by scientists who have
dedicated their lives to fighting AIDS," Van Der Horst said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
