<HEADLINE> Uganda to Export More Power to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Kenya are negotiating
to increase the former's power sale to the latter from the current
30 megawatts to 80 megawatts, a Ugandan official said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Uganda now exports to Kenya up to 30 megawatts power a day and
stops exporting during the peak hours between 6:00 p.m. to 10:30 p.
m. when the demand in Uganda is high," Godfrey Turyahikayo, energy
commissioner of Uganda's Energy and Mineral Development Ministry,
told Xinhua in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's power export to Kenya has increased after the Unit 11
of the Owen Falls Extension Project with a capacity of 40
megawatts was launched in May this year.
</P>
<P>
"When the Unit 12 at the expanded power generating dam in the
Ugandan city of Jinjia is launched early next month, Uganda will
be able to export to Kenya up to 30 megawatts during peak hours
and totally 80 megawatts a day," he added.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has an installed capacity of 240 megawatts. With the
Unit 11 and 12 of the Owen Extension Project being brought on line,
Uganda will be able to export more power to its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Uganda exports three megawatts of power to Rwanda and five
megawatts to Tanzania. Kenya is the leading importer of its power,
contributing 750,000 U.S. dollars to the Ugandan treasury every
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
