<HEADLINE> U.S. Investigates Police Beating of Black Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Justice Department
Thursday started an investigation into the beating of a black
suspect by police officers in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno said at her weekly news conference
that U.S. Attorney has commenced an investigation.
</P>
<P>
A dozen police officers were seen beating Thomas Jones after a
chase Wednesday. The scene was captured by videotape from a news
helicopter and broadcast around the nation.
</P>
<P>
Police and witnesses said officers chased Jones in a stolen car
until it crashed, then exchanged gunfire with him.
</P>
<P>
Jones was able to commandeer a police car and fled before he
was cornered and subdued, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
This event has reminded people of the 1991 Rodney King case
that ignited rioting in Los Angeles after four white officers were
acquitted of state charges. Two officers were eventually convicted
of federal civil rights charges.
</P>
<P>
Jones was in fair condition Thursday at Temple University
Hospital with injuries to his abdomen and arms.
</P>
<P>
An officer who was shot was in good condition at Hahnemann
University Hospital.  
</P>
