<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Underlines Lessons on Srebrenica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Five years after the fall
of Srebrenica in Bosnia, the U.N. Security Council Thursday
underlined the importance of the lessons on Srebrenica, a U.N.-
designated safe area where the fall led to the killing of
thousands of innocent civilians, and reiterated its commitment to
the full implementation of the Dayton Peace Accords.
</P>
<P>
The president of the Security Council, Patricia Durrant of
Jamaica, invited the members of the 15-nation Council to observe a
minute of silence in honor of the victims of the Srebrenica murder
when the Council met in an open session on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
In a commemorative statement on Srebrenica, Durrant described
the tragic events as "one of the worst civilian massacres in
Europe since the end of World War II."
</P>
<P>
"The tragic events at Srebrenica must not be forgotten," the
statement said. "The Council regrets the deplorable events and
recalls its resolve to ensure that justice is carried out fully
through the work of the International Criminal Tribunal for the
Former Yugoslavia, and that the crimes are not repeated in the
future."
</P>
<P>
"The Council stresses the importance that lessons be learned
and acknowledges the (U.N.) Secretary-General's report on
Srebrenica," the statement said. "The Council reiterates its
commitment to the full implementation of the Dayton Peace Accords
and to the establishment of multi-ethnic democracy and the rule of
law throughout the territory of the former Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has expressed his "deepest
regret and remorse" on the eve of the fifth anniversary of the
Srebrenica massacre.
</P>
<P>
"The tragedy of Srebrenica will forever haunt the history of
the United Nations," Annan said in speech here Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 7,000 Muslims are believed to have been executed by
Serb forces after the fall of the U.N.-proclaimed safe zone in
July 1995.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 bodies have been found so far in the vicinity of
Srebrenica, but only 70 have been identified.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot undo this tragedy, but it is vitally important that
the right lessons be learnt, and applied in the future," Annan
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The principal lesson of Srebrenica is that we must oppose evil
not with compromise but with "implacable resistance," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
In a report last November, Annan admitted U.N. errors, but
maintained that the collective international community was
responsible for the massacres.
</P>
<P>
Srebrenica has become the symbol of the suffering caused by
the Bosnian war, which cost 200,000 lives between April 1992 and
November 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
