<HEADLINE> U.N. to Hold More Talks With Taliban on Women's Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Coordinator for
Afghanistan, Erick de Mul, is planning to travel to Kabul on
Sunday to continue his discussions with the Taliban authorities on
the recent issue concerning the employment of women in
international organizations, U.N. said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Erick Mul traveled to Kandahar Wednesday and had talks with
the Taliban, the biggest warring party in Afghanistan, on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
U.N. said Erick had positive talks with the Taliban and the
issue concerning the employment of women by the U.N.in Afghanistan
was in the process of being resolved.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban issued the edict last week which banned Afghan
women from international nongovernmental organizations and U.N.
agencies in the country. Should it be put into effect, it would
have a detrimental effect on the United Nations 's capacity to
deliver aid to Afghans.
</P>
<P>
While women are restricted from working in the Taliban-
controlled areas of Afghanistan, in the past, exceptions have been
made for women working in the health sector and other essential
roles within national and international organizations. Without
their continued participation, a number of humanitarian assistance
program for Afghanistan would be severely constrained.
</P>
<P>
U.N. said that a major concern has been the possible effect on
the World Food Program's bakery projects. The World Food Program
is currently feeding 1.5 million Afghans in the country.
</P>
