<HEADLINE> Romania: Bisons to Be Returned to The Wild </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is footing a
project in Romania for returning to the wild of the bisons from
the reservations, the local daily Romania libera reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the project nursed by Romania's Forests Authority and the
Institute for Forest Research and Administration, six bisons
living in the northeastern Vanatori Neamt Forest Park will be
released into a nearby forest enclosure in a first stage of this
project.
</P>
<P>
The welcoming enclosures will become increasingly large, up to
200 hectares, in order to help bisons feed by themselves.
</P>
<P>
A specialist from a country where bisons managed to stay alive
in the wilderness, will come over to set the conditions for this
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Neamt reservation managers hope this first stage where bisons
living in captivity would try to adapt to the wilderness will
become successful during the next five years and be expanded into
other areas of Romania's Carpathian Mountains and thus join the
area across the northern border of the country.
</P>
<P>
The bison was an extinct species in southern Carpathian
Mountains since the 17th century and in eastern Carpathians since
the 19th century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
