<HEADLINE> U.N. Highlights Significance of Peace Agreement For Palestinian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Special
Coordinator for the Middle East Peace Process, Terje Roed-Larsen,
on Thursday released a report on the Palestinian economy which
details many of the major challenges that lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling the report, the Special Coordinator said "Real long
term growth of the Palestinian economy requires sustained private
investment and increased exports.
</P>
<P>
Only a viable peace agreement would provide the stability and
predictability necessary to achieve these goals, he said.
</P>
<P>
 The talks at Camp David represented a unique window of
opportunity to achieve a lasting peace, and to ensure a durable
prosperity for the Palestinians, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
 In his report, the Special Coordinator also highlighted the
importance of a more rapid pace of institutional and fiscal reform
by the Palestinian Authority
</P>
<P>
 The U.N. report, referring to developments in 1999, finds the
following:
</P>
<P>
 -- Real GDP and GNP growth of 6 percent and 7 percent
respectively;
</P>
<P>
 -- A 15 percent increase in employment in Israel;
</P>
<P>
 -- A 7 percent increase in domestic private sector employment;
</P>
<P>
 -- A 14 percent increase in planning construction activity;
</P>
<P>
 -- Significant growth in new company registrations;
</P>
<P>
 -- A 32 percent increase in outstanding bank credit to
business;
</P>
<P>
 -- A 12 percent increase in donor assistance;
</P>
<P>
 -- A 3 percent increase in the average daily wage.
</P>
<P>
 Despite these improvements, the report noted that Palestinian
exports and non-construction private investment, the two
fundamental components of sustained growth and development, remain
depressed, lagging behind general economic gains.
</P>
<P>
 Furthermore, while per capita income grew 2 to 3 percent in
1999, it remained 10 percent below its 1993 level.
</P>
<P>
 The report also noted the slower growth in 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
