<HEADLINE> Putin Urges Comprehensive Measures on Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
said that large-scale social rehabilitation, an effective
political process, resources and sacrifices in addition to force
are needed to resolve the problem of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody must understand that the choice is between resolving
this issue now or flinching it, withdrawing and facing the same
problems later with casualties much higher than now," Putin said
in an interview that will appear in the Friday edition of the
Izvestia newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Russian federal troops launched a military campaign against
rebels in the breakaway republic last September in the wake of
armed Chechen incursions into neighboring Dagestan and a series of
apartment explosions that left over 300 Russian dead in Moscow and
two other cities.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale military actions have ended in Chechnya, but the
remaining rebels, estimated at around 2,000, are mounting sporadic
attacks on federal troops and police units.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of federal soldiers and policemen were killed last week
in a series of rebel suicide bombings.
</P>
<P>
"Patience, delicate and balanced action are needed in tackling
problems such as those that we are facing in the North Caucasus. A
high price will have to be paid for every mistake."
</P>
<P>
If cut loose by Russia, Chechnya would not be free. Instead, it
would be taken over by extremists and immediately become a
springboard for attacks on Russia, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Russian media reported earlier Thursday that federal aircraft
flew 56 bombing and reconnaissance missions in Chechnya over the
previous 24 hours, targeting rebel strongholds there.
</P>
<P>
As tensions persist in and around Chechnya, security measures
have been stepped up elsewhere across Russia.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, all vital systems and facilities have been put under
increased control, the Interfax news agency reported, quoting
sources with the municipal government of the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Yuri Luzhkov has instructed the district authorities to
strengthen the security of educational establishments, medical
centers, transport and communication systems, bridges and
industrial enterprises, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
