<HEADLINE> Egypt Resumes Regular Flights to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A passenger plane of Egypt's national
carrier flew to Libya on Thursday, resuming regular flights between
the two countries after a hiatus of eight years due to
international sanctions imposed on Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The EgyptAir plane carried 71 passengers and 62 civil aviation
officials, who will discuss some remaining technical issues with
their Libyan counterparts, the state-run Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
EgyptAir board chairman, Mohammed Fahim Rayyan, said the
Egyptian company will have three flights each week from Cairo to
Libya -- two to the capital Tripoli and one to the Mediterranean
city of Benghazi.
</P>
<P>
The number of flights may be increased if needed, Rayyan said.
</P>
<P>
Libya's first plane in eight years touched down at Cairo
International Airport last Saturday, carrying 11 passengers and a
delegation of Libyan civil aviation officials. The Libyan Arab
Airlines (LAA), the national carrier, will make 12 return flights a
week between the two countries including seven linking Tripoli and
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
LAA's two flights will link the Mediterranean cities of Benghazi
in Libya and Alexandria in Egypt in addition to two weekly flights
between Benghazi and Cairo and one between Sabha, 600 kilometers
south of Tripoli, and Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of air link between Egypt and Libya came more
than a year after the United Nations Security Council suspended an
eight-year air embargo on Tripoli following the handover of two
Libyans suspected of the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am airliner over
Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Officials on both sides have attributed the delay to technical
and commercial reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
