<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Oldest Shipwreck Ready for Exhibition in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The oldest shipwreck of the world,
known as the Uluburun Wreck, will be put on display as of July 23
at the Underwater Archaeology Museum at Turkey's western Aegean Sea
port of Bodrum, Anatolia News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The wreck of a Syrian vessel sunk into the waters of the
Mediterranean in about 1306 B.C. while transporting the goods it
loaded from Egypt to the Greek Mediterranean island of Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
It is presented to the public 18 years after its discovery off
the shores of Uluburun, after which the wreck was named, near
Turkey's southern Mediterranean port of Kas.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists said the Uluburun Wreck "is a matchless, living
Late Bronze Age example" that has survived all the way through the
ages, with its rich load and other important equipment.
</P>
<P>
The museum, which was termed as one of the "nine most important
museums of Europe," hails the Uluburun Wreck as its "pillar of
underwater archaeology."
</P>
<P>
Director of the museum Oguz Alpozen, one of the first divers to
reach the wreck, said the wreck will be displayed in the same way
as when it was discovered so that visitors can see how it looked
under the water with its load and everything aboard.
</P>
<P>
"Enthusiasts and museum officials from the United States,
Britain, France, and Greece will attend the inauguration to be made
by Culture Minister Istemihan Talay," said Alpozen.
</P>
<P>
The 20-meter long vessel was discovered by a diver in 1982 at
some 60 meters below the sea surface and was recovered in 25,000
dives carried out between 1984 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
The vessel is a fine example of the Late Bronze Age maritime
creation, lighting up archaeologists about that age with the items
it had been carrying.
</P>
<P>
A golden seal of Queen Nefertiti, royal consort of Pharaoh
Akhenaten (reigning 1379-1362 B.C.) of Egypt famous for her
colorful limestone bust now in Berlin Museum and her support for
the pharaoh's religious reforms, is considered the most important
item of the load.
</P>
<P>
Another seal, carrying the name of a later pharaoh, supports
estimation that the ship might have sunk in 1306 B.C.
</P>
<P>
A small note pad, with two boxwood leaves attached to each other
with an ivory hinge, is considered the oldest book of the world.
</P>
<P>
The golden seal of Nefertiti and many other important items
found in the wreck will be displayed at a separate hall in the
museum.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the "astonishing" load also include 10 tons of
Cyprus copper, 1 ton of pure tin, over 150 round and flat bullions
of different sizes, shapes, and colors, one ebony tree, one cedar
tree, over 100 amphoras, 1 ton of resin collected from different
types of Middle Eastern and Aegean trees.
</P>
<P>
It was also loaded with many other delicate craftworks such as
processed ivory pieces, sea shells, turtle shells used to make
musical instruments, ceramic and metal mouthpieces, ostrich shells
used to make vases and cups, ceramics, wine cups, gold and silver
bracelets and necklaces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
