<HEADLINE> Writethru: 85 Killed in India in Incessant Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some 80 people died in Maharashtra and five were killed in
central and north Gujarat as heavy downpour disrupted rail and
road traffic and inundated many areas, local police said.
</P>
<P>
In worst-hit Mumbai, 50 people, including six women and 10
girls, were killed in a landslide in Ghatkopar area and 40 injured
in a mudslide triggered by torrential rains at Chrag Nagar
Wednesday night, according to the Press Trust of India.
</P>
<P>
Several areas in northwest and northeast Mumbai were plunged in
darkness last night with the Bombay Suburban Electricity Company
switched off a number of sub-stations and feeders as a safety
measure.
</P>
<P>
The state government has declared a holiday for college and
school students in Mumbai Thursday in view of the inclement
weather.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of office workers were stranded at various points as
trains services continued to be affected following water logging
on the tracks. Buses had to be diverted at several places because
of flooding of low-lying areas.
</P>
<P>
Northern Railways Thursday canceled and rescheduled some trains
to Mumbai following heavy rains which lashed the metropolitan
since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, The Indian Meteorological Department has forecast
heavy rainfall during the next 48 hours in several parts of
Maharashtra, Gujarat and several other states. 
</P>
