<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Scientists Call for Coordinated Anti-AIDS Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- African scientists on
Thursday called for coordinated efforts to find an affordable
vaccine for the HIV/AIDS virus by 2007.
</P>
<P>
They were unanimous at the launch of the African Strategy for a
HIV vaccine at the ongoing 13th International AIDS Conference in
east South Africa's Durban city, finding that a vaccine was the
only way to win the war against HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The strategy which was drawn up in Nairobi, Kenya, on June 14
aims to bring together scientists on the continent to coordinate
their efforts to find an affordable vaccine.
</P>
<P>
They spoke out against what they termed the "scientific
exploitation and manipulation" of Africa by international agencies.
This would also assist in curbing the uncontrolled spread of the
disease in Africa, where 24 million people were already infected.
</P>
<P>
Professor Malekgapuru Makgoba, president of the African Medical
Research Council, said there was the need for a coordinated
African effort to find a vaccine, and to achieve this, the
scientists on the continent had to work together and exchange
information.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize we have a serious epidemic in Africa. In the
midst of this epidemic we have African scientists all doing their
own thing to find a vaccine. The fact that we are not working
together allows us to be exploited by international agencies,"
Makgoba said.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of trials for an African vaccine started in
Uganda last year. Kenya, in partnership with the United Kingdom,
will start trials for another possible vaccine in December, while
South Africa and the United States trials will begin next January.
</P>
<P>
While pledging the commitment of the African scientists to
work together to find the vaccine, Makgoba stressed the need to
work with urgency to the solution to the epidemic threatening to
wipe the nation on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"We are racing against time," he said.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, these scientists want at least one vaccine in
its final stages of testing by 2007.
</P>
<P>
Two main strains of the virus were found in Africa, and
African scientists will focus on developing a "broad" vaccine
which could effectively deal with the disease, according to
Makgoba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
