<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two U.S. Telecom Giants Scrap Merger Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. telecom giants WorldCom
and Sprint announced Thursday they were scrapping their merger
plans, citing opposition from U.S. and European antitrust
authorities.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the companies said that "the set of conditions
ultimately demanded by the U.S. Department of Justice would
compromise the customer and financial benefits of the merger."
</P>
<P>
Late last month, Attorney General Janet Reno announced the
Justice Department was suing to block the 129-billion-U.S.-dollar
deal. The Justice Department contended that the merger of the
second- and third-largest U.S. long-distance carriers would leave
millions of Americans paying more for less service.
</P>
<P>
The merger was also opposed by European regulators, who judged
it would corner too much of the Internet. WorldCom offered to sell
Sprint's high-capacity Internet network to alleviate the
regulators' concerns, but the move was considered insufficient.
The two companies had already pulled their merger application in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Both the Westwood, Kansas-based Sprint and the Clinton,
Mississippi-based WorldCom said the Department of Justice had
informed them it would not be able to go to trial before January
2001. Even if the companies were successful in that trial,
approval by the Federal Communications Commission and the European
Commission would still be needed.
</P>
<P>
"Given the competitive nature of the marketplace, prolonged
delay and uncertainty would not be in the best interest of our
shareholders, employees or customers," Sprint Chairman and Chief
Executive William Esrey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
WorldCom announced plans to acquire Sprint last October,
triggering an investigation by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
In the U.S. long-distance market, WorldCom's share amounts to
19 percent and Sprint's eight percent. And in the market for
Internet backbone services, WorldCom controls 37 percent and
Sprint 16 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
