<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Egyptian survey indicated that 45,000 Egyptian
scientists emigrated to foreign countries in the recent five years.
Among them are 600 scientists of rare specialities, including 94
specialists in nuclear engineering, 26 in nuclear energy, 28 in
chemistry, 25 in astronomy and space science, 28 in biology, 72 in
laser uses and 93 in electronics and software, according to the
survey by the Egyptian Scientific Research Academy.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The World Bank has recently finalized a feasibility
study pertaining to the financing of five development programs in
Morocco to the value of 212 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
These programs provide for setting up projects aimed at
reinforcing the infrastructure of villages, overhauling the
educational system, developing the agricultural field, combatting
poverty and updating the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Internet cafe which was set up by industrialists in
Kayseri province, central Turkey, has contributed to the
development of trade with many countries.
</P>
<P>
Kayseri Chamber of Commerce Director Erdal Cinar said that
industrialists in Kayseri had become used to e-commerce at the
Internet cafe which was opened at the Organized Industry Region
seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
The industrialists have started trading with European countries,
Israel and other countries of the world.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- Qatar planned to step up total oil output to about 1
million barrels per day (bpd) by 2001, according to a senior Qatari
official with the General Qatari Oil Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Qatar's current daily oil production is 854,000 barrels while
its quota under the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) is around 659,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government put off a program designed to raise
oil production in light of the slump in crude price then. The
decision by OPEC in March 1999 to slash output pushed up the crude
price almost three-fold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
