<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Inspects Fire-Safety Compliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Fire officials in Beijing launched
a 10-day inspection of fire safety compliance locally starting
from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The emergency inspection on the first day was targeted at
several big furniture businesses and a gas bottling plant in the
southern suburb.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the Beijing Municipal Fire-fighting Bureau said
sites to be reviewed in the next few days include those places
producing, storing or selling flammable and explosive chemicals,
big shopping malls and markets, public recreation centers, and
other places that routinely accommodate large crowds.
</P>
<P>
Any units with sub-standard fire-fighting equipment would be
required to make improvements within a set period of time.
</P>
<P>
Beijing reported 2,289 fires in the first five months of this
year, resulting in 17 deaths, 37 injuries and 7.1 million yuan in
economic loss, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Beijing had 5,395 fires last year which killed 53 people and
injured 92 others. Direct economic losses caused by these fires
totaled 31.65 million yuan (4.35 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
