<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Customs Vows to Suppress Illicit Fuel, Cigarettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Customs and
Excise Department has devised a multi-pronged approach to address
the illicit fuel and cigarettes problem, a customs official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Acting Assistant Commissioner of Customs and Excise Simon
Wong Shiu-ming revealed the Department's strategy and enforcement
actions against illicit fuel and cigarettes activities at a press
briefing.
</P>
<P>
It has also endeavored to eradicate and suppress illicit fuel
and cigarettes at all levels, i.e. import, export, distribution,
retail and use, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, the Anti-Illicit Cigarette Task Force with
a complement of 84 officers was set up. It incorporated the then
40-man-strong Anti-Cigarette Smuggling Task Force.
</P>
<P>
Up to 30 June, 57 large-scale operations (including joint
operations with the Hong Kong Police and Environmental Protection
Department) against the sale and storage of illicit fuel have been
mounted, resulting in the arrest of 248 persons and a total
seizure of 587,991 liters of illicit fuel.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the suppression of illicit cigarettes, various region-
wide operations aiming at enforcement action against street
peddling of illicit cigarettes were launched resulting in the
seizure of 10.4 million sticks of cigarettes with a value of 13.7
million HK dollars (1.7 million U.S. dollars) over the past three
months.
</P>
<P>
During these three months, a total arrest of 75 buyers were
made which represents a 74 percent increase comparing to the
arrest of 43 buyers in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the department seized a total of 239 million sticks of
illicit cigarettes with a value of 301 million HK dollars
representing an increase of 120 percent comparing with the seizure
of 104 million sticks in 1998.
</P>
<P>
A total of 8.57 million liters of illicit fuel have been seized
in 1999 with a value of 39.57 million HK dollars which marks a 64
percent increase when compared to the seizure of 5.23 million
liters in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
