<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition Showcases Aesthetics of Japanese Arts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition featuring 100
pieces of fine artifacts from the Tokyo National Museum opened at
the Hong Kong Museum of Art Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
The month-long exhibition, titled "Japanese Art of the 19th
Century - Treasures from the Tokyo National Museum," reflects not
only the cultural trends in the Edo and Meiji periods in 19th
century Japan, but also the aesthetic taste of Japanese living
around that time.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Director of Leisure and Cultural
Services Paul Leung Sai-wah said the exhibition was mounted as an
exchange program between the Hong Kong Museum of Art and the Tokyo
National Museum of Japan.
</P>
<P>
He also said Museum of Art was honored to be the first Chinese
museum to establish an exhibition exchange program with the Tokyo
National Museum.
</P>
<P>
Last October, the Museum's treasures of Chinese antiquities
were sent to the Tokyo National Museum to mark the opening of its
refurbished Hyokeikan. The exhibition was well received in Japan.
In exchange, the Tokyo National Museum organizes the present
exhibition on Japanese art.
</P>
<P>
"Our focus lies on the 19th century when Japan progressed
steadily towards modernization. It would be meaningful to observe
from the present display how Japan opened up to the West and still
managed to maintain its own national characteristics in art," said
Leung.
</P>
<P>
Since the Tang Dynasty (618 - 907), Japan was deeply influenced
by Chinese culture and gradually developed its own distinctive art
forms and styles. From 19th century onwards, Japanese arts became
known by the West and their frequent cultural contacts paved way
for a new look in the modern Japanese art world.
</P>
<P>
Featuring a rich mixture of works in seven categories, namely
painting, calligraphy, ceramics, lacquer ware, metalwork and
textile, the exhibition reflects the artistic merits representing
various schools and styles flourished in 19th century Japan.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is jointly presented by the Leisure and Cultural
Services Department and the Agency for Cultural Affairs, Japan,
and organized by the Hong Kong Museum of Art and the Tokyo
National Museum and sponsored by Japan Airlines Company Limited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
