<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Coalition Government Partially Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Mesut Yilmaz, leader of Turkey's
junior ruling partner Motherland Party (ANAP), was appointed on
Thursday as state minister and deputy prime minister for the
European Union affairs while Cumhur Ersumer was dismissed from his
post as deputy prime minister but retained the post of state
minister for energy.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet was partially reshuffled at the request of Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit. It was accepted by Turkish President Ahmet
Necdet Sezer and was issued in the Official Gazette on the same
day.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz's appointment was within expectations but it was not
clear why Ersumer was dismissed from the post of deputy prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Ecevit held 40-minute talks with Yilmaz, who was
recently cleared of corruption allegations in the parliament, and
announced that Yilmaz will take up the position in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Thursday's confirmation of Yilmaz's appointment by the
president, Ecevit said Yilmaz will be responsible for public
institutions and organizations within the framework of the
preparation process to the European Union (EU) membership.
</P>
<P>
But he said foreign relations related with the EU will still be
carried out by the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
As an EU candidate, Turkey is stepping up its accession process
to the European club.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz was born in Istanbul in 1947. He graduated from Ankara
University's Political Science Faculty in 1971 and later studied at
Germany's Koln University for two years.
</P>
<P>
As a founding member of ANAP, he acted as deputy chairman of the
party and was elected as a parliamentarian in 1983. Eight years
later, he was elected as the leader of ANAP at the party's general
congress and acted as prime minister for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Last year when Democratic Left Party (DSP) leader Ecevit formed
the current coalition, together with Deputy Prime Minister Devlet
Bahceli's Nationalist Action Party (MHP) and Yilmaz's ANAP, the
ANAP leader rejected a role in the cabinet as he was facing eight
corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, who acted as prime minister three times, was accused of
abusing power for self-interests during his tenures.
</P>
<P>
Last month, tension was brewing in Ankara once again as three
MHP deputies joined the opposition deputies in a parliamentary
investigation commission in a bid to file Yilmaz to the Supreme
Court over allegations of graft.
</P>
<P>
The move soured relations between ANAP and MHP, the two junior
partners within the coalition, and jeopardized the coalition's
stability which Ecevit has strived for and is imperative for his
economic reforms program.
</P>
<P>
It was alleged that the MHP and ANAP are trying to damage each
other as part of their election strategy as both parties are aiming
to woo nationalist and conservative votes in the absence of the
pro-islamic opposition Virtue Party (FP).
</P>
<P>
The possibilities of an early election still exist because the
Turkish constitutional Court will decide whether the FP is the
successor to the defunct Islamic Welfare Party or not in October.
</P>
<P>
If the court makes a "yes" verdict, the FP will be closed and 70
deputies of 103 FP deputies in Parliament will be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Turkish Constitution, if five percent (about
28) of the 550-seat Parliament's deputies are absent, the country
should be forced into an early parliamentary election within three
months.
</P>
<P>
After the decision to file Yilmaz to the Supreme Court failed in
the parliament, the coalition left behind the tension, if
tentatively.
</P>
<P>
Also, the decision in the parliament meant to have cleared
Yilmaz of the corruption allegations, paving the way for his entry
into the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
After offering the position in the cabinet for Yilmaz, Ecevit
said , "Mesut Yilmaz is an experienced statesman with time in the
government. This is a great advantage, ensuring coordination among
public and private institutions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
