<HEADLINE> Estrada to Be Granted Special But Limited Powers for Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A measure seeking to give
Philippine President Joseph Estrada special but limited powers to
speed up the rehabilitation of war-torn Mindanao will be filed
Monday before the House of Representatives, a press official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential palace briefing, Press Undersecretary Mike
Toledo said the bill will be filed by House Majority Leader
Eduardo Gullas when Congress opens it special session on July 17.
</P>
<P>
According to Toledo, Estrada is seeking for special but limited
powers so that his pro-poor administration can expedite projects
geared to transform Mindanao into an economic powerhouse following
the fall of Camp Abubakar, the main stronghold of the separatist
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), into the hands of the
government.
</P>
<P>
"It is intended to set in place or in motion policies to ensure
that Mindanao becomes a competitive and investor-friendly region,"
Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
"The special but limited powers will have a life span of about
two years, and we will ensure that there will be no abuse in the
exercise of such powers," he added.
</P>
<P>
Toledo said a special oversight committee composed of five
members of the Senate and the House each will be created to
monitor the exercise of these powers and activities of the
Mindanao Coordination Council (MCC), which held its first meeting
here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The presidential palace, he noted, is "quite confident" that
the measure will pass the scrutiny of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada is committed to bringing genuine and lasting
peace and economic development to Mindanao and reverse the decades-
old official neglect of the southern island.
</P>
<P>
Estrada wants to transform Mindanao into a major financial
center and the country's next food basket, Toledo added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
