<HEADLINE> World Bank Closes Seoul Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will close its Seoul
office Friday, two years and three months after helping South
Korea overcome its financial crisis which was caused by corporate
bankruptcies and bad loans in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
As South Korea does not need additional loans and agreements
with the bank have all been carried out, the Seoul office will
close as of Friday, the Ministry of Finance and Economy said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank opened its office in April 1998, appointing Sri-
Ram Aiyer as the country director in South Korea to review the
loan program.
</P>
<P>
It has loaned South Korea a total of 7 billion U.S. dollars
since the financial crisis in 1997 and provided 40 million U.S.
dollars through the ASEM (Asia-Europe Meeting) Trust Fund, which
was set up in 1998 to assist southeast Asian countries to overcome
the financial crisis, to support technology development.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government and the bank will maintain ties
through advisory assistance and dissemination of South Korean
lessons to other developing nations, the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Economic Growth to Reach 8.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's economic growth is
expected to reach 8.6 percent this year despite a slower growth
rate in the latter half, the Korea Development Institute (KDI)
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the government-run think tank warned that the economy
may face a drastic downturn from next year if the ongoing
corporate restructuring fails to produce a substantive outcome.
</P>
<P>
"Should the government only focus on mitigating the credit
crunch through expansion of liquidity without removing the
insolvent factors of enterprises and financial institutes, the
national economy may face a serious setback," said KDI in a report.
</P>
<P>
Time is running out for South Korea to complete the corporate
restructuring as it will become more difficult to carry out
reforms under an economic decline, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The coming six months will be the critical period that will
determine the success or failure of the corporate restructuring,
it noted.
</P>
<P>
It put the restructuring in business sector over that of the
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
"Although many financial institutions managed to decrease debts
due to injection of public funds, the debts incurred by
enterprises have remained the same as the pre-crisis level," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The think tank underlined the need to take resolute steps to
normalize the management of insolvent companies through transfer
of loans to investment.
</P>
<P>
It also forecast that the growth rate of South Korea's GDP,
which stood at 12.8 percent and 9.5 percent in the first and
second quarters, will decrease to 7.2 percent and 5.6 percent in
the third and fourth quarters, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Private sector consumption is projected to reach 8.2 percent on
an annual basis as the economic growth rate will drop in the
second half of this year amid decreases in virtual income and
stabilized asset prices, it said.
</P>
<P>
Exports are expected to continue to increase while imports will
also rise sharply due to increases in domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The current account surplus is likely to reach 9.5 billion U.S.
dollars this year, a drastic decline from last year's 25 billion.
</P>
<P>
The KDI estimates that the consumer commodity prices will
remain stable at 2.1 percent on an annual basis but the
inflationary pressure would rise in the latter half of this year
because of rising wages and public utility fares.
</P>
<P>
With the relatively favorable economic climate at present, the
corporate restructuring needs to be accelerated in the upcoming
six months to one year period, the last chance to achieve the
objective, added the institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
