<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall Sharply in Tokyo on Sogo's Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell sharply in Tokyo
Thursday following the collapse of Japanese department store chain
Sogo Co.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined 305.23 points, or 1.
76 percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 17,036.90.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 30.24 points, or 1.88 percent, to 1,574.
16.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section grew to 789.96 million shares
from Wednesday's 778.49 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sogo's failure hit the banking sector, as many banks have made
loans to Sogo which may be unrecoverable, while the construction
sector was also weak.
</P>
<P>
The mining, textile and insurance sectors declined sharply.
The precision instruments industry was the only gainer among the
exchange's 33 business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Food makers also weakened in the wake of food-poisoning
outbreaks involving major dairies.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers 1,100 to 210, with 88 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
