<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homesick Ambassadors Trounce Chinese All-Stars to Win ABA Super League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- the NBA Ambassadors, homesick yet
highly-motivated, gave the demoralized Chinese All-Stars a 103-68
beating in the deciding match of the best-of-three Asian
Basketball Association Super League here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The visitors dominated the court in every quarter and had once
extended their lead by 38 points even though two teams looked to
be on the same par after splitting their previous six encounters.
</P>
<P>
The two teams split the first two games of the finals. The
Ambassadors won 95-78 here on Monday and the Chinese All-Stars,
all Chinese internationals, made it one-all by beating the
Ambassadors 111-103 in Tianjin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Let's go home now," said the Ambassadors' top scorer Mike
Jones, who admitted he was homesick as much as his teammates after
leaving home for a month to play the ABA Super League which kicked
off on June 8.
</P>
<P>
Jones, who scored 19 points including 10 in the second quarter,
was one of six two-digit Ambassadors players. He also grabbed
seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Rasul Salahuddin, who garnered 33 points in Game Two,
contributed 16 points Thursday night. Wayman Strickland also
turned in 16 points. Matt Steigenga, Jason Dixon and Ross Land
snatched 14, 12 and 11 points respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dixon pulled down 11 rebounds to be the top rebounder of the
visitors.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassadors was rotating nine players, of whom Dixon had
teh longest playing time-26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
China's 7-footer center Wang Zhizhi, a 1999 second-round draft
pick of the Dallas Mavericks, pumped in 24 points and grabbed 11
rebounds, but he alone was not enough to save the All-Stars who
was outshot and out-rebounded by the faster and more agile
Americans.
</P>
<P>
Yao Ming, who stands 7-3, scored only 4 points in the first
half and was benched in the third quarter after his jaw was
bleeding.
</P>
<P>
China was beaten in every aspect. The Ambassadors snatched 40
rebounds against China's 29. China had 16 turnovers and 28 fouls
while the Americans had only 8 turnovers and 19 fouls.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassadors, coached by Hall of Fame point guard Nate "Tiny
" Archibald, had been pressuring the Chinese from teh very
beginning, leading 22-12 at the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The visitors, led by Jones, widened their lead to 55-25 at
halftime and kept a 78-49 lead after the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese had lagged by 38 points in the fourth quarter
before the Americans slackened off a bit in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
"We have learned a lot from the NBA Ambassadors," said Chinese
head coach Jiang Xingquan. "We know how many weaknesses and
loopholes we have through the ABA Finals."
</P>
<P>
China will take on the American squad, hailed as "Dream Team",
in the opener of the Olympic basketball competition this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
