<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Israelis Support Barak's Peace Move: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- More Israeli people have shown
their support for Prime Minister Ehud Barak's peace move, but said
it is hard for Barak to bring home a peace agreement with the
Palestinians from the Camp David summit, the results of an opinion
poll indicate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted on 522 Israelis by a local firm for Israel
Radio on Tuesday when the Camp David summit began, showed support
for Barak's peace move has risen by 8 percent to 60.1 percent from
the previous poll on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Among those interviewed, only 30.9 percent thought the summit
will end in a deal and 18.5 percent did not know or refused to
answer. Some 53.7 percent respondents said Barak has a mandate to
make concessions, up from 53 percent in Sunday's poll.
</P>
<P>
The poll gave Barak a boost if elections were held right now
against former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, with 45.5 percent
saying they will vote for Barak and 34.2 percent for Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The results of the new poll represents a significant jump for
Barak, who trailed Netanyahu in a poll taken last month.
</P>
<P>
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat are holding their
summit at Camp David near Washington with U.S. President Bill
Clinton to solve the key issues such as the status of Jerusalem,
borders, refugees, Jewish settlements and water.
</P>
<P>
The summit is aimed at reaching a framework agreement on all
these issues ahead of a September 13 deadline for a final peace
deal.
</P>
<P>
Three coalition partners left Barak's government on Sunday in
protest against Barak's attendance at the summit, leaving Barak
with a minority in the Knesset (parliament). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
