<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Forms Committee to Deal with Deviationists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has formed an Action
and Monitoring Committee to handle investigations relating to
deviationist groups and the detention of their members, Minister
in the Prime Minister's Department Abdul Hamid Othman said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This is the authorities' new approach in checking the spread of
deviationist teachings in the country, he told reporters at
Parliament House lobby here.
</P>
<P>
He said the government finds it necessary to adopt the new
approach to avoid the recurrence of arms heists as those staged by
members of the Al-Ma'unah deviationist group in Gerik in the
northern state of Perak early this month.
</P>
<P>
"We now have to monitor all existing religious organizations,"
he said, urging the Registrar of Societies to alert the Department
of Islamic Advancement and the police about religious
organizations indulging in dubious activities.
</P>
<P>
He said that the authorities could come up with a special
program to rehabilitate members led astray by deviationist groups
to return to true religious teachings.
</P>
<P>
The committee is made up of police and officers of the
department of Islamic advancement and state religious affairs
departments.
</P>
<P>
Earlier only religious department officers were involved in
investigating suspected deviant groups, he said, adding the
previous process was rather time-consuming as it involved much
persuasion to steer those concerned back to the correct path.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Moves to Upgrade Skills of Women Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government pushed
Thursday for the upgrading of women workers' skills to help them
land in remunerative and better paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
Labor Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma said it is currently hard
for women without training or education to find employment.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report from the Bureau of Labor and Employment
Statistics (BLES Laguesma said women employed with elementary or
low level of education decreased from 44 percent of the total
employed women in 1989 to 36.6 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said the BLES data showed that employed women with high
school and college education rose from 26.6 percent and 25 percent
in 1989 to 31.7 percent and 28.5 percent in 1999 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Data also showed that more employed women were agricultural
workers accounting for 28.1 percent, followed by women in sales
for 26.1 percent, service for 15.9 percent, production for 11
percent, clerical for 6.9 percent, and managerial position for 1.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The data indicated the need to train women in various skills to
enable them find better jobs or engage in livelihood, Laguesma
stressed.
</P>
<P>
To address the need, Laguesma said the Department of Labor and
Employment (DOLE) has intensified its programs to promote the
employability of women workers.
</P>
<P>
The DOLE's Bureau of Women and Young Workers, in its report to
Laguesma, said it focused its assistance to women along with the
efforts to train women in entrepreneurial and other skills.
</P>
</TEXT>
