<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Inflicts Serious Socio-Economic Losses: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries'
wealth will be reduced by 15 to 20 percent over the next 10 years
as a result of HIV/AIDS, according to new research presented on
Thursday by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
This will impose serious socioeconomic costs on the economies
of these countries, the world bank said in a report at the 13th
International Conference on HIV-AIDS in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Citing growing evidence, the report said lower economic growth
and increased poverty threatens to form a vicious cycle in which
HIV-AIDS drives many families into deepening poverty, and at the
same time poverty speeds the spread of HIV.
</P>
<P>
Breaking this cycle will require not only greatly increased
investments in more effective HIV prevention and care, but also
more effective measures to combat poverty, participants agreed,
said Robert Hecht, UNAIDS Associate Director for Policy, Strategy
and Research.
</P>
<P>
World Bank's Vice-President Callisto Madavo announced that the
World Bank was developing a 500-million-U.S.-dollar fund to help
African governments pay for expanded AIDS programs.
</P>
<P>
"Dealing with the epidemic requires money and commitment -- and
it also requires knowledge", said Madavo.
</P>
<P>
"We will be drawing on what you have learned in helping
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Three new studies presented at the symposium suggest that high
levels of HIV infection do significantly reduce growth, making it
harder for countries to reduce poverty and to generate the
resources needed to cope with the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Southern African countries are the hardest hit by HIV/AIDS,
with an estimated 25 million AIDS sufferers. In South Africa, an
estimated 20 percent of the population is infected with HIV, and
because of this, researchers forecast that the country's GDP will
be 17 percent lower by 2010 than it would have been without an
epidemic. Individual families will also find their incomes reduced.
</P>
<P>
Another study on Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago also warned
that AIDS would significantly harm economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a study of diamond-rich Botswana, which has the
world's highest incidence of HIV, with 36 percent of its adult
population infected, warned that the country would face "a rapid
increase in the number of very poor and destitute households in
the coming decade."
</P>
<P>
Although income from diamond exports would cushion the impact
on GDP growth, per capita household income for the poorest quarter
of all households is likely to fall by 13 percent, the study said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
