<HEADLINE> Thailand to Send 52 Athletes Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has chosen 52 athletes to
take part in the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney in September,
according to the country's Olympic Committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Somluck Kamsing, who won a gold at the 1996 Olympics, will try
to defend his featherweight boxing title. He will also carry the
Thai national flag at the opening ceremony on September 15.
</P>
<P>
Other title hopes include tennis star Tamarine Tanasugarn,
would number 45. She made it to the fourth round at the Wimbledon
Championships for the third successive year last week.
</P>
<P>
Thai boxers are expected to bring more medal success to the
country, which won its first ever gold four years ago through
Somluck.
</P>
<P>
Pakpoom Jangponak, Pongsit Wiengwises and Suban Pannon are
among the top boxers tipped to strike medals in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
As incentives for athletes, the Government will award three
million baht ( 75,000 US dollars) cash prize to gold-medal winners;
two million baht (50,000 dollars) for silver and one million (25,
000 dollars) for bronze.
</P>
<P>
The 52 Thai athletes will take part in 13 sports of athletics,
swimming, badminton, boxing, rowing, windsurfing, shooting, table
tennis, beach volleyball, weightlifting, tennis, archery and
yachting. 
