<HEADLINE> Pipeline Fire Victims Appealed to Come Out for Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Authorities of the southern Nigeria'
s Delta State, where some 250 people died in a fuel pipeline fire,
have appealed for the wounded to come forward for hospital
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Most of the injured have reportedly sought help from
traditional doctors because they fear arrest on suspicion of
stealing oil if they attend hospitals, reported Nigerian press on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the state's capital Asaba, Governor James Ibori appeal on a
local radio late on Wednesday that they would not be arrested.
</P>
<P>
He expressed horror at the scenes of the blast which occurred
along a stretch of pipeline between the villages of Adeje and
Ovire Court outside Warri, a major oil town in the south of Africa
's largest oil-exporting country.
</P>
<P>
The explosion happened when people were using buckets to
collect petrol flowing from the pipeline after it had been
punctured by thieves on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The blaze flared up again after a second smaller explosion on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Warri quoted a local senior police
officer as saying that "an exact toll is unlikely to be clear for
some time but we know more than 250 people have died."
</P>
<P>
Doyin Okupe, President Olusegun Obasanjo's spokesman,
reportedly called on Wednesday the disaster an "avoidable tragedy"
and blamed greedy business operators for encouraging dangerous
pipeline vandalism. 
