<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Pepper Export Up Remarkably </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam exported 31,000 tons of
pepper for 127 million U.S. dollars in the first half of this year,
recording year-on-year increases of 29 percent and 35.5 percent,
respectively, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pepper has become one of Vietnam's major export earners.
According to the Ministry of Trade, the country's six-month export
of pepper equaled about half the turnover of rice and coffee,
doubled the export turnover of rubber and was sixfold that of tea.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's pepper is now exported to 40 countries and regions
including Singapore, Laos, China, Denmark, France, Holland, Poland,
the United Arab Emirates and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam harvested around 36,000 tons of pepper in 1999,
doubling the figure for 1998. The country is to gather an
estimated 38,000 tons of pepper this year, of which 34,000 tons
will be exported.
</P>
<P>
Around 48,000 hectares of land is now under pepper cultivation
in Vietnam's southern provinces of Binh Phuoc, Dong Nai, Ba Ria-
Vung Tau, Tay Ninh and Kien Giang and in the central provinces of
Dac Lac and Quang Tri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
