<HEADLINE> 70% Zimbabwean Families Live Below Poverty Line  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The living conditions of
Zimbabweans have worsened with up to 70 percent of families now
living beyond their means owing to the prevailing economic
hardship, the weekly Business reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the Consumer Council of Zimbabwe (CCZ) shows
that a family of six needs at least 9,000 Zimbabwean dollars (236
U.S. dollars) to buy a month's basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
CCZ regional manager Victor Chisi said many workers could not
afford this, which meant that the majority of people were living
below the poverty datum line.
</P>
<P>
Chisi said, "This basically means that a lot of Zimbabweans go
without basic consumer needs and goods."
</P>
<P>
"This has been worsened by manufacturers and suppliers of
consumer goods who now increase prices of commodities arbitrarily
in pursuit of their sectoral needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Consumers have been reeling from economic hardship
characterized by a high inflation rate of 70 percent and a severe
shortage of foreign currency, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
