<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A Brazilian official will succeed
the current Angolan executive secretary of the Community of the
Portuguese-speaking Countries (CPLP) , according to the Angolan
foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
Dulce Maria Pereira, who is currently the president of
Palmares Cultural Foundation, a subordinate body of the Brazilian
Ministry of Culture, will be confirmed for the new post at CPLP's
upcoming summit this month in the Mozambican capital of Maputo.
</P>
<P>
Pereira, born on November 10, 1954, in Sao Jose do Rio Preto,
is a Brazil University graduate majoring in visual anthropology,
planning, development, communication and technology.
</P>
<P>
Marcolino Moco, former Angolan prime minister, has been acting
as executive secretary of the CPLP since 1996 when the seven
Portuguese-speaking countries, at the suggestion of Brazil,
established this international organization in Lisbon, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
CPLP groups Portugal, Brazil, Angola, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau,
Cape Verde, Sao Tome and Principe, with a population of 200
million and an area of 10.7 million square kilometers. 
</P>
