<HEADLINE> Kenya, Egypt in Trade Dispute  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The trade dispute between Kenya
and Egypt has taken a new twist with Egypt vowing to institute a
33-percent levy on Kenyan tea following a 33-percent suspended
duty on Egyptian products levied by Kenya, Kenyan media reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Ambassador to Kenya Refaat al-Ansary Wednesday told
the press here that the consignment of Kenyan tea currently held
at Port Said in Egypt would not allowed into the Egyptian market
until the tariff stalemate is resolved.
</P>
<P>
Egypt on Monday moved to block Kenyan tea imports into its
domestic market after Kenya imposed the suspended duty on Egyptian
rice which was one of the recommendations in Kenya's June 15
budget.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said there were 52 commodities from Egypt to
Kenya which do not enjoy preferential treatment under the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
Both Kenya and Egypt are COMESA members.
</P>
<P>
Refaat al-Ansary appealed to Kenyan authorities to remove all
barriers to bilateral trade and stick to COMESA regulations on
tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said Egypt had consulted the matter with Kenyan
President Daniel arap Moi who agreed to take up the issue with the
relevant ministries to ensure it was brought to a conclusion
agreeable to both countries.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that currently a big trade imbalance exists
between the two countries with Kenya being the beneficiary. Egypt
is the third biggest consumer of Kenyan tea after Pakistan and
Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
