<HEADLINE> Chirac Writes to Philippine President on Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A letter from French President
Jacques Chirac calling for an end to the hostage crisis in the
Philippines will be delivered to his Philippine counterpart Joseph
Estrada on Thursday, Chirac's spokeswoman Catherine Colonna said.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, who will travel to
Manila after the Group of Eight (G-8) meeting in Japan, will hand
the letter to Estrada, asking for his help to end the 12-week-long
hostage crisis in the southern Philippine island of Jolo as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim rebel group Abu Sayyaf has been holding 37 hostages
for 12 weeks and kidnapped three French television journalists
last week. The 37 hostages include five French citizens, four
Germans, two Finns, two South Africans and one Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Chirac expressed deep concern about the
situation of the 40 hostages and his hope that "all would be done
to seek a happy and quick solution," said Colonna.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting last week with the family of one of the French
hostages, Chirac said that he will make an initiative "at European
level" to seek the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine, scheduled to arrive in Manila Thursday with German
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer and Finnish Foreign Minister
Errki Tuomioja, will ask the Philippine authorities to "intensify"
talks with the Muslim rebel group.
</P>
<P>
They will also ask the Philippine authorities not to resort to
force to liberate the hostages and to keep the "humanitarian
corridor" open for sending food and medicines to the hostages.
</P>
</TEXT>
