<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Reopen Second Largest Pyramid of Famous Giza Trio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will soon reopen the second
largest pyramid of the Giza trio on the outskirts of Cairo after a
year-long facelift involving scraping salt, lipstick and graffiti
off the inner walls, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The restoration work on the 4,500-year-old pyramid of Khafra,
also known as Khefren, has just finished and tourists will now see
an even more impressive display than before, said Zahi Hawas,
director of Giza pyramids and antiquities.
</P>
<P>
The lighting system inside the 136-meter high structure has been
rearranged in a way that enhances the magic and mystery for
visitors, the English-language newspaper quoted Hawas as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cracks have been patched up by using sand, water and rock chalk,
the same building materials used by the ancient Egyptians, and
cameras will now monitor tourists to catch graffiti artists and
visitors who leave lipstick kisses and marks on the walls, the
guardian of the pyramids said.
</P>
<P>
The salt deposits resulted from the water vapour in the breath
of visitors, each of whom produces about 20 grams, Hawas said. He
added a new ventilation system has been installed to reduce
humidity and improve the air quality for visitors to the monument.
</P>
<P>
Hawas said a limit will be set on the number of visitors as it
had been when the largest pyramid of Khufu (Cheops) was reopened in
June 1999 after restoration. Before it was closed for a facelift,
Khufu's Pyramid attracted more than 4,000 tourists each day,
prompting safety concerns. Now, only 300 people are allowed in
every day.
</P>
<P>
The pyramid of Menkaure (Mykerinos), the smallest of the famous
trio on the Giza plateau, is next in line for temporary closure
under a restoration scheme for the three pyramids started in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Knesset (Parliament) members from the ultra-Orthodox
Shas party defied the Supreme Court ruling Wednesday on former Shas
leader Aryeh Deri and vowed that he "will always lead" the
movement, even as he enters prison to serve a three-year term.
</P>
<P>
Knesset faction chairman Yari Peretz explained that the faction
decision does not mean that Deri will return to the chairmanship,
but rather that he will be "a partner and active" in party affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Shas faction met Wednesday afternoon in "urgent" session to
discuss the court ruling. A statement released afterward said "we
are all in anguish over the appalling discrimination," repeating
the theme that Deri has not been given a fair trial because of his
Sephardi origin.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will propose a "relatively
high degree of autonomy" for the Palestinian neighborhoods in
Jerusalem, as well as an exchange of territory in which some Jewish
neighborhoods near Jerusalem will be incorporated into the Holy
City in exchange for the transfer of some of the Palestinian
neighborhoods to the area of the Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Alpher, Barak's special advisor on media relations for
the summit talks, said "everything related to Jerusalem is on the
table" but that the Jerusalem issue is the hardest in the
negotiations, and it is not certain that agreement will be reached.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's former Shas party leader Aryeh Deri will spend his
last month of freedom before entering prison on August 13 to serve
a three-year term by appearing in a series of Shas rallies around
the country, in order to take leave of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court Wednesday upheld the Shas leader's conviction
of bribery, but reduced his sentence from four to three years. He
can be free in two years, depending on his good behavior.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the court hearing, Deri went to Shas spiritual
leader Rabbi Yosef's home, where he called for "unity" in Shas
ranks and an end to the party's factionalism. He also attacked
Barak's government and then the secular Israelis, "who cannot bear
the idea that the Sephardi public is returning to religion."
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak issued a brief statement
from Camp David following the Supreme Court's ruling on former Shas
party leader Aryeh Deri's appeal on Wednesday, saying he "regrets
that the Deri family is facing a difficult period, but Israel is a
law-abiding state and we must all respect the decision of the
court."
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said it was a "sad moment" when,
for the first time in Israel's history, an individual who served as
a cabinet minister, will serve time in prison. Beilin urged the
politicians "to display public responsibility and prevent
incitement and rifts in the society." 
</P>
</TEXT>
