<HEADLINE> Indonesian Former President Undergoes Final Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former president
Soeharto underwent investigation again on Thursday for corruption
charges at his residence in Central Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"Prosecutors gave Soeharto some simple questions due to the
poor condition of Pak Harto (Mr. Soeharto)," Soeharto's lawyer
Juan Felix Tampubolon told reporters after the questioning, adding
that Thursday's investigation was the final one.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the Attorney General's Office (AGO) Yushar Yahya
told Xinhua that there was a new development in Soeharto's case.
</P>
<P>
"But for the time being we think that is enough," he added
without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Yahya also said that dossier of Soeharto in corruption cases
will be submitted to the court before Soeharto's house arrest
status expires on August 10.
</P>
<P>
"And in connection with Soeharto's healthy condition, the court
has to decide whether or not Soeharto would be tried. Just wait,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was suspected of abusing power and authority by
issuing decrees and government regulations to amass funds through
seven tax-free charity foundations he set up and chaired during
his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
He was put under house arrest and has been banned from leaving
the country since May.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Marzuki Darusman has pledged to try Soeharto
before August 10 this year or before the country's highest
decision-making body of the People's Consultatives Assembly (MPR)
hold its annual session scheduled for August 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
