<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 137 in Manila Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of people killed in the
dumpsite avalanche that occurred Monday in Payatas, Metro Manila,
has climbed to 137 as of 02:00 a.m. Thursday, the Philippine
government said.
</P>
<P>
The National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) said 89
survivors were found and 37 persons were injured, adding that 386
families or 1,625 persons have been evacuated to safe places from
the dumpsite.
</P>
<P>
But the NDCC said authorities are still having a hard time
estimating the number of those still buried in the pile of mud and
garbage.
</P>
<P>
Ismael Mathay, mayor of Quezon City, said earlier that more
than 100 shanties were buried in the landslide in the Payatas
dumpsite.
</P>
<P>
There were about 50,000 people residing in Payatas. The open
dumpsite was scheduled to be closed in October 1999, but the
closure was held back for lack of an alternative disposal site for
Quezon City's more than 700 tons of daily garbage.
</P>
<P>
Due to a week of continuous monsoon rains, the tons of garbage
must have loosened which resulted in its erosion and eventually
became a landslide, said Mathay.
</P>
<P>
The military officials said military dogs used in the Mindanao
campaign would soon be deployed in assisting military and rescue
personnel in locating bodies buried.
</P>
<P>
The dogs were earlier used in sniffing bombs and land mines
planted by the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Defense Secretary and NDCC Chairman Orlando
Mercado said the government could not give a time frame as to when
recovery efforts would stop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0167 </DOCNO>
