<HEADLINE> New Zealand Welcomes Release of Hostages in Fiji </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Helen Clark and Foreign Minister Phil Goff said here Thursday
night that the release unharmed of the hostages in Fiji came as "a
tremendous relief."
</P>
<P>
But they said Fiji "remains far from a return to democratic
government."
</P>
<P>
In a government press release, Clark and Goff noted there's
evidence that Fiji is sliding towards anarchy.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand has signaled clearly in the last few weeks that
the installation of a government in Fiji which lacks a basic
commitment to democracy will lead to the application of a number
of measures against Fiji," they said.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to urge the Great Council of Chiefs to show
leadership and display wisdom in signaling a desire to return to a
democratic government and constitution as soon as possible," they
added.
</P>
<P>
"If there are signs of goodwill, New Zealand will work with,
encourage and support a new administration. If not, and there is
instead an ultra-nationalist regime denying basic human rights to
many, New Zealand will bring into force a range of sanctions," the
New Zealand leaders said. 
</P>
