<HEADLINE> ASEAN Lawmakers Meet to Discuss Anti-Waste Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers from the members of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) Thursday began
a two-day meeting here to study ASEAN countries' policies on
hazardous wastes control.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the special meeting
convened by the ASEAN Inter-Parliamentary Organization (AIPO),
Singapore Speaker of Parliament Tan Soo Khoon said ASEAN should
not sacrifice benefit of the environment for economic and
industrial gains.
</P>
<P>
"The economic and industrial developments must not be carried
out at the expense of the environment," Tan said.
</P>
<P>
He called on ASEAN members to adopt effective anti-pollution
and management programs in tandem with economic and industrial
growth to ensure the benefit of the 500 million ASEAN people.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from the eight AIPO members, together with Brunei
observer delegation, are attending the AIPO Ad Hoc Committee
Meeting on Comparative Study of ASEAN National Legislative
Policies on Hazardous Wastes Control.
</P>
<P>
AIPO, founded in 1977, includes Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Thailand, Vietnam and Singapore.
Myanmar and Brunei are permanent special observers to the
organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
