<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Women to Get Drug Preventing HIV Transmission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Two drugs to be administered
through the vagina are to be tested in Uganda for their
effectiveness in stopping sexual HIV transmission, the New Vision
daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory tests have indicated that the drugs kill HIV and
have potential to prevent transmission during sex, Lut Van Damme,
consultant for UNAIDS and the World Health Organization, was
quoted as saying in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
She said the trial would begin by the end of this year, and it
will be carried out by a joint program run by the Uganda Virus
Research Institute and the Medical Research Council in the Ugandan
city of Entebbe on women from the general population.
</P>
<P>
The germ-killing substances, referred to as microbicides, would
provide an affordable women-controlled HIV-prevention method,
Damme said during the ongoing international AIDS conference in
Durban, South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
