<HEADLINE> Shanghai B-share Market Up at Thursday Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai B-share market index
shot up 1.79 points, or 3.23 percent, to 57.24 on Thursday,
clocking its largest gains after two weeks of consolidation.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 18.28 million US dollars, which was 146.69 percent
more than Wednesday's total.
</P>
<P>
The market traded with a positive tone as a broad-based rally
was ignited by a trade report, which helped restore confidence and
brought investors to today's dealings with renewed enthusiasm,
according to Homeway, China's leading on-line financial and
securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
China's exports rose 38.3 percent in the first half of 2000
from a year earlier to 114.5 billion US dollars, according to
figures from the general customs. Imports increased 36.2 percent
to 102.1 billion US dollars, leading to a first-half surplus of
about 12 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports of garments, steel and electrical products showed the
biggest growth, whose shares got extra boost today.
</P>
<P>
Rising issues outpaced falling shares by 40 to 2, with 3
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Sh Refrig Comp (900910.SS) climbed 9.35 percent to 0.234 US
dollars, while Ch 1st Pencil (900905.SS) rose 6.46 percent to 0.
128 US dollars. Wing Sung (900906.SS) slipped 1.45 percent to 0.
136 US dollars, Matsuoka (900955.SS) fell 0.36 percent to 0.548 US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The market is steadily gaining strength amid investor optimism
for further signs of an improving economy while keeping an eye on
earnings prospect as usual.  
</P>
</TEXT>
