<HEADLINE> Writethru: Fiji's Hostage Crisis Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's deposed Prime Minister
Mahendra Chaudhry and 17 of his colleagues were released on
Thursday after being held in hostage for 56 days, the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) reported.
</P>
<P>
Chaudhry and his colleagues were then escorted to the Red Cross
headquarters and reunited with their families, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister's wife, Vimira Chaudhry, was among a
crowd of about 300 friends, media and onlookers, many of whom
cheered and clapped as all of the former hostages arrived.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another former prime minister and now chairman of
the Great Council of Chiefs, Sitiveni Rabuka, is expected to
announce the chiefs' nomination for the country's president later
Thursday evening, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Fiji's Great Council of Chiefs issued an ultimatum to
the coup plotters over the release of the hostages, according to
the ABC.
</P>
<P>
They told George Speight's coup group that if they did not free
the hostages soon, they would lose immunity from prosecution,
promised in an agreement aimed at solving the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Before the release of the remaining hostages at the parliament
compound in Fiji's capital Suva, Speight conducted a traditional
ceremony asking for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
Chaudhry was given a bowl of kava and shook hands with Speight
before leaving, the ABC reported.
</P>
<P>
Journalists had been refused entry to the parliament compound
and army checkpoints are also turning back the media.
</P>
<P>
Police have shut off the area in front of the Red Cross
headquarters where the 18 former hostages would be given a medical
check-up.
</P>
<P>
Under an accord reached by Speight and Fiji's military last
Sunday, the 50-strong Great Council of Chiefs was to meet on
Thursday to name a new president and vice president.
</P>
<P>
In return, Speight was committed to releasing all the hostages,
including Chaudhry, Fiji's first ethnic Indian prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
