<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Ports Urged to Upgrade Service Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian ports has been
urged to improve productivity and upgrade service quality through
information technology (IT) applications such as computerized
container terminal management systems and web-based transaction
systems.
</P>
<P>
To become a major regional hub, the major ports in the country
should improve their operational efficiency, manpower training,
infrastructure development and ship planning, the Productivity
Report 1999 released here Thursday by the National Productivity
corporation (NPC) said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian ports were affected by the 1998 economic downturn and
the volume of cargoes handled in that year came down by 13.3
percent to 159.299 million tons against 183.645 million tons in
1997.
</P>
<P>
There was a marginal decrease in shipcalls to the country's 13
major ports with 51,183 ships in 1998 from 59,214 ships in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the performance of the port industry continued to
improve throughout the year following steps taken by port
operators and the government, including implementing programs to
improve productivity and quality at all levels of port operations
and greater promotion of local ports.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, added value per employee grew 1.8
percent to 87,440 ringgit (23,010 U.S. dollars) in 1998 thanks to
management efficiency, positive work attitude or quality programs.
</P>
<P>
And as for the competitiveness of labour cost, added value per
labor cost declined 2.78 percent in 1998, labor cost per employee
grew 3.1 percent while unit labor cost increased 2.1 percent,
indicating that higher labor cost did not commensurate with added
value creation, the NPC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
