<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Union, Africans' Dream in New Century by Zhang Dacheng and Liu Hao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 13 (Xinhua) -- As African leaders met in the
Atlantic town of Lome, Togo, to convene the 36th summit of the
heads of state and government of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU), establishment of a more integrated regional body, the
African Union, to replace OAU has come on the top of their agenda.
</P>
<P>
The OAU, founded by the forerunners of Pan-Africanism in the
early 1960s, has been playing a key role in guiding Africans in
wiping out colonialism and racism and ushering in a new era of
self-reliance and development.
</P>
<P>
Now that nearly four decades have passed, Africa found itself
in a tight corner in a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
When the world economy developed so fast in the tide of
globalization, Africa has been dragged into endless armed
conflicts, facing such burdens as a great amount of refugees,
heavy debt, unbridled spread of HIV/AIDS and uncontrolled
population growth among others.
</P>
<P>
To face ever-increasing new challenges from the outside world,
African leaders gradually have reached the consensus that, Africa
needs a continental organ which is more powerful than OAU in all
sectors.
</P>
<P>
A solution was found on September 9, 1999 when the OAU leaders
gathered in the small town of Sirte, Libya and approved the well-
known Sirte Declaration which advocates the establishment of the
African Union.
</P>
<P>
Following deliberations at ministerial level, the leaders who
attended the 36th OAU summit from July 10-12, this year, signed
the Draft Constitutive Act of the African Union, officially
starting the process for establishing the Union.
</P>
<P>
The main characteristic of the African Union is that with a
more reasonable organizational structure, it was authorized more
power and rights. As a leading continental organ, the African
Union will be in charge of the political, economic, military,
social and cultural affairs of the continent to accelerate
political, economic and social integration and to maintain peace,
security and stability.
</P>
<P>
Leaders at the OAU Lome summit have agreed to improve the
African Union by setting up it first, although some of them are
worried that conditions are not ripe for such a speedy stride in
establishing the Union.
</P>
<P>
The OAU summit decided to hold the fourth extra-ordinary summit
in March next year in Sirte, Libya again to review the
ratification by member states of the Draft Act, which says that
the Union can be set up only when the Act is ratified by more than
two thirds of the member states.
</P>
<P>
Once coming into being, the African Union is expected to
sharpen Africa's competitive edge and to prevent the continent
from being marginalized.
</P>
<P>
At the very beginning of a new century as well as a new
millennium, the Africans are sparing no effort in establishing
their Union, a major step forward to their long-expected dream of
a Unites States of Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
