<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unlawful Driving More Likely Involved in Road Accidents: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 12 (Xinhua) -- One of every five fatal car
crashes in the United States involves a driver who is not properly
licensed, a traffic safety group reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The findings by the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety are an
analysis of 183,749 fatal crashes between 1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
The study concludes that 20 percent of all fatal crashes
involves drivers who were driving with an invalid (suspended,
revoked or canceled) license, who were unlicensed, or who were of
unknown license status.
</P>
<P>
In addition, about 18 percent of the drivers in the "suspended
license" grouping had been convicted of drunk driving during the
three years prior to the fatal crashes.
</P>
<P>
A driver with a suspended or revoked license is 3.7 times more
likely than a driver with a valid license to be involved in a
fatal crash. Meanwhile, an unlicensed driver is 4.9 times more
likely than a driver with a valid license to be involved in a
fatal crash, the study said.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, New Mexico was the state with the
highest rate (23.7 percent) of improperly licensed drivers
involved in fatal crashes during the five-year study period,
followed closely by Washington D.C. (23 percent) and Arizona (23
percent).
</P>
<P>
The study, carried out by Lindsay Griffin and Sandra DeLaZerda
of Texas A&AMP;M University, indicated attempts to change human
behavior might not be the best solution for reducing unlawful
driving.
</P>
<P>
Instead, a better solution may be found in vehicle sanctions or
modifications that physically impede unlawful driving through
vehicle impoundment, electronic driving licenses or alcohol
ignition interlocks, which require the driver to provide a breath
sample every time he or she attempts to start the automobile, the
study said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tech Firms Increase Spending on Magazine Advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A report issued on Wednesday
shows that U.S. magazine advertising climbed nearly 20 percent in
June from the year-ago level, with technology and Internet
companies boosting their spending by more than half.
</P>
<P>
The Publishers Information Bureau, a magazine industry trade
group, said magazine advertising last month totaled 1.495 billion
U.S. dollars, a 19.8-percent gain from a year earlier. The number
of ad pages during the month climbed 17.2 percent to 24,408.
</P>
<P>
For the first six months of the year, magazine publishers'
advertising revenues went up 17 percent to 8.39 billion dollars
and total ad pages were up 14.4 percent at 121,171, the New York-
based group said.
</P>
<P>
Spending by technology companies climbed 55.7 percent to 183
million dollars last month and ad pages gained 74.3 percent to 3,
529, the group said. For the first six months of the year, ad
spending in the sector gained 35.5 percent to 869 million dollars
and pages were up 55.4 percent to 16,369.
</P>
<P>
Tech companies outspent automotive firms, which reduced their
advertising outlays during the month by 7.5 percent to 152 million
dollars for a 10.1-percent decline in pages to 2,034. During the
six months, spending by automotive companies fell 6.1 percent to
823 million dollars and pages were down 7.5 percent to 10,977.
</P>
<P>
"There has been significant growth in magazine advertising in
the first half of 2000," said Christine Miller, executive vice
president and chief marketing officer for the group.
</P>
<P>
"The numbers indicate the ongoing synergy between magazines and
the Internet, which is especially evident in the technology sector,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
The group represents more than 240 U.S. publishers with
approximately 1,400 titles, as well as more than 80 international
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
