<HEADLINE> U.S. Troops Allegedly Discharge Toxic Chemicals Into S. Korean River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Forces Korea (USFK) has
discharged a large amount of toxic chemicals into the Han River
via drain pipes from its Yongsan headquarters camp in central
Seoul, said Green Korea United (GKU) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, the GKU accused the USFK of secretly
discharging some 480 bottles of solution mixed with formalin and
methanol into Han River which runs through the central part of the
capital city.
</P>
<P>
The GKU showed as evidence photos, empty bottles and remaining
solution.
</P>
<P>
Formalin and methanol are poisonous chemicals that can lead to
mental unrest and memory loss. Long-term exposure can kill fish
and other marine beings.
</P>
<P>
The USFK is said to have used the chemicals in preserving the
corpses of its servicemen who died from various accidents in South
Korea before repatriation.
</P>
<P>
The GKU said it will demonstrate in front of the USFK camp and
the U.S. embassy starting Friday to protest against such
irresponsible acts.
</P>
<P>
After the news conference, the South Korean Environment
Ministry asked the USFK to confirm the allegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
