<HEADLINE> Turkey to Return Picasso Paintings to Owners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Culture Minister Istemihan
Talay has promised to return two smuggled Picasso oil paintings to
their real owners, reported Turkish Daily News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two paintings "La Fermiere" and "Dora Maar" were seized by
police in Izmir, southwest of Turkey, in two separate operations
while smugglers were trying to sell them, by chance, to undercover
police last month.
</P>
<P>
Pablo Picasso (1881-1973), a Spanish painter, moved to settle
down in Paris in 1904 and later became a pioneer painter of French
modernist school.
</P>
<P>
Talay told reporters in Izmir Wednesday the two paintings are
now kept in Ankara's State Painting and Sculpture Museum.
</P>
<P>
"Some countries are claiming to be the owner of these paintings
and have applied to the Foreign Ministry asking for return of the
works," he said. "Turkey will carefully examine these international
claims and if these countries can prove ownership according to the
international criteria, these paintings will be returned to them."
</P>
<P>
France, Russia and Kuwait have reportedly claimed ownership of
the paintings and approached the Turkish Foreign Ministry for the
matter.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that "La Fermiere" was stolen from the Kuwaiti
Emirate Palace during the 1991 Gulf War and later fell into the
hands of an international smugglers' ring.
</P>
<P>
Talay said experts' reports have established their originality
and there is no need for further tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
