<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The usage of information
technology (IT) in terms of the extent and intensity among
Malaysia's manufacturing industries showed an improvement over the
last two years, according to a Productivity Report 1999 released
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report released by the National Productivity Corporation
said IT was widely used for administrative functions and the
majority of the companies are using IT intensely to support such
functions.
</P>
<P>
All sub-sectors of the manufacturing sector recorded strong
growth, achieving more than 90 percent in IT usage for
administrative functions.
</P>
<P>
To encourage further growth in the manufacturing sector, the
government has initiated a Worldwide Manufacturing Web to provide
a conducive environment for value-added manufacturing using IT.
</P>
<P>
With the web, the government is enhancing the potential of
manufacturing companies to use advanced IT in their activities,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Manufacturing companies should take heed of the government's
move to consider IT strategically and improve on existing
capabilities towards greater efficiency and competitiveness," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector, the most important sector in the
economy with its contribution to the gross domestic product
amounting to more than one third, is expected to register a
productivity growth of 4.4 percent, employment growth of 3.5
percent and output growth of eight percent this year. 
</P>
