<HEADLINE> New Zealand Opposes Nuclear Fuel Shipments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister of Foreign
Affairs and Trade Phil Goff said here Thursday that his country
remains firmly opposed to all shipments through its Exclusive
Economic Zone (EEZ) of nuclear materials.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to reports that Britain and Japan had reached
an agreement on the fate of a mixed oxide fuel shipment that Japan
had rejected on arrival last year. It is understood that Britain
will now accept the return of the fuel.
</P>
<P>
In a government press release, Goff said his government has
made it clear to both Japan and Britain that New Zealand is
opposed to all such shipments and wants them to stay away from the
country.
</P>
<P>
"We accept that the risk of an accident is low, but the
consequences of an accident would be immense," the minister said.
"If there must be shipments, we expect prior warning. We expect
that the shipment should remain outside our EEZ."
</P>
<P>
The transport of such a hazardous substance raises the risk to
New Zealand, Goff said, stressing: "We believe that the transport
states should accept liability and responsibility to pay
compensation for any accidents."  
</P>
</TEXT>
