<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia Reach Agreement on Rubber Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Thailand,
Malaysia and Indonesia have reached an agreement on rubber trade
to prop up rubber prices and eliminate price-cutting among the
world's three largest rubber producers, the Thai News Agency (TNA)
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Agriculture and Cooperatives Minister Arkom
Engchuan was quoted as saying that the agreement was reached at a
recent meeting between officials of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, the three countries would use central prices,
which will be jointly set up based on an agreed currency, for
exports of their rubber products and would not sell their products
at prices lower than the jointly set-up levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
They would also cooperate in exchange of information on rubber
trade, stock control, and the opening up of rubber markets, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the three countries will meet in Malaysia
next month to discuss and set up the central prices to be
presented before the upcoming ministerial meeting of the three
countries, which will be held in Thailand's southern city of
Phuket in September, Arkom added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
