<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Firms Study More on Competitors Than on Customers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Organizations in Malaysia are
placing more emphasis on research on their competitors instead of
customers or suppliers, according to the National Productivity
Corporation (NPC) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The NPC said in its Productivity Report 1999 that about 20.5
percent of the organizations surveyed indicated that they carried
out research on their competitors while only 16.3 percent carried
out research on customer preference and evaluating suppliers
electronically.
</P>
<P>
The findings came from a survey on "Electronic Commerce
Applications in Malaysia 1999" carried out by the NPC in
collaboration with Universiti (University) Malaya to explore the
extent of usage and implementation of e-commerce in various
sectors of the Malaysian economy.
</P>
<P>
The survey focused on trends of e-commerce applications in
marketing, advertising, customer support service, delivery and
payment.
</P>
<P>
The survey comprised 590 respondents, of which 12 percent
represented the trade sector, 8.6 percent finance and 7.5 percent
electrical &AMP; electronics.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that organizations were keen to use e-
commerce to provide better services to their customers, thus
improving the relationship between them, which was important for
business, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
