<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: OAU Leaders Poised to Face Challenge  by Liu Hao and Zhang Dacheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The first annual summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) in the new millennium with the
theme of integration has paved the way for Africa to confront the
great challenges of peace and development.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day summit which ended on Wednesday in the
Togolese capital, over 30 heads of state or government, together
with representatives of member states, discussed issues ranging
from AIDS, debt, refugees to poverty which have long plagued
Africa.
</P>
<P>
They seemed to run with time by reaching consensus on the draft
treaty of African Union at the last minute as they agreed that
there is no way but a closer union that can save Africa from being
marginalized by the globalization trend, though there was serious
debate over the speed, the nature and form of the Union.
</P>
<P>
At the closing ceremony, 25 member states inked signature on
the Draft Constitutive Act of the Union which will replace the OAU.
However, the act shall not come into force until two-thirds of the
OAU's 53 members ratified it.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the act signaled another decisive step to
accelerate integration process after the special summit in Sirte,
Libya, last September, which decided to create an African Union.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the Union will be established at a special
summit in Sirte next March at the earliest date.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders believed that peace and security should be
the foundation on which the African Union was to be built.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing that persistence of conflicts and wars is seriously
undermining the security and stability, and gravely hampering the
development efforts, they reaffirm their strong resolve to make
the year 2000 a year of peace, security and solidarity in Africa
in accordance with the Algiers Declaration at last summit in July
1999.
</P>
<P>
They were committed to intensify actions for peace and to
support efforts aimed at the peaceful settlement of conflicts in
Africa, particularly through the strengthening of the OAU
Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, they urged the U.N. and international
community to pay necessary attention to the management and
resolution of conflicts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
With recurrent conflicts, widespread poverty, heavy external
debt burdens and the largest number of refugees and people
infected with HIV in the world, Africa is rightly expecting more
assistance from the international community.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the African leaders are aware that whatever the
help is given, their own responsibility is more important and it
is high time that Africans assume it so that peace and stability
prevail in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
