<HEADLINE> 1stlead: Remaining Fijian Hostages Released EDS: Adds Coup Leader Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's deposed prime minister
Mahendra Chaudhry and 17 of his colleagues were released on
Thursday after 56 days as hostages, the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation (ABC) reported.
</P>
<P>
Chaudhry and his colleagues were handed over to the Red Cross,
the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
Before the release at the parliament compound in Fiji's capital
Suva, the coup leader George Speight conducted a traditional
ceremony asking for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
Chaudhry was given a bowl of kava and shook hands with Speight
before leaving, the ABC reported.
</P>
<P>
Journalists had been refused entry to the parliament compound
and army checkpoints are also turning back the media.
</P>
<P>
Police have shut off the area in front of the Red Cross
headquarters where the 18 former hostages would be given a medical
check-up. 
</P>
