<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Productivity Set to Grow by 4.2 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's productivity has
been forecast to grow by 4.2 percent this year from 3.9 percent
last year, the National Productivity Corporation (NPC) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 4.2 percent productivity growth this year against the
forecast year-on-year increase of three percent can be expected
amidst further growth resulting from strong economic fundamentals,
a conducive investment climate and sound macro-economic policies,
NPC said in its 1999 productivity report released here.
</P>
<P>
The productivity level increased to 22.026 billion ringgit (5.
79 billion U.S. dollars) last year against 21.207 billion ringgit
(5.58 billion dollars) in the previous year, it said.
</P>
<P>
"To achieve higher productivity growth, emphasis will have to
be placed on enhancing Total Productivity Factor (TFP) and
application of appropriate technology in both the private and
public sectors," the corporation said, adding in this respect, the
Knowledge Economy (K-economy) could be the most appropriate
strategy to enhance productivity.
</P>
<P>
This strategy could be expected to generate added value per
unit of factor of production and hence lead to a higher
productivity, it said.
</P>
<P>
The most important sector, manufacturing, is expected to
register a productivity growth of 4.4 percent, employment 3.5
percent and output eight percent. The sector's performance is
expected to be stimulated by greater demand, domestically and in
the global market.
</P>
<P>
The construction sector is expected to post a productivity
growth of 3.7 percent, employment 1.3 percent, output 5.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
The finance sector is expected to record a productivity growth
of 4.4 percent, employment 1.0, and output 5.4 percent, while the
trade sector is expected to register a productivity growth of 1.7
percent, employment 2.8, and output 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, productivity contributed 70 percent, while
employment contributed 29.0 percent to the annual Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) growth of 5.6 percent, the NPC said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's productivity last year outstripped that of several
selected major Organization of Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) countries where Japan saw a 2.3 percent growth,
the United States 2.3 percent, and Germany 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that to improve productivity growth and competitiveness,
small and medium-sized industries need to further increase their
added value generation through adoption of higher technologies and
venturing into high value-added products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
