<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Army Will Not Be Withdrawn From "Flash Points" in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's army and police will not
withdraw their units from identified "flash points" in Harare
despite widespread condemnation of perceived strong-arm tactics by
the troops, The Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police Spokesman Chief Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena
Wednesday said in a statement that the public's claims of army
brutality had not been substantiated.
</P>
<P>
He said as far as he knew the officers deployed to the suburbs
were under instructions not to harass anyone but to suppress
lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers have been accused of imposing "marshal law" over wide
swatches of Harare and other parts of the country, beating up
revelers at beer halls and people found in groups, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Bvudzijena said that police were sure that calling off the
operation would result in a resurgence of post-election political
violence.
</P>
<P>
About 30 people were arrested in the recent days after sporadic
incidents in suburbs. 
</P>
