<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Reports Profit Increase for 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Motorola Inc., the world's
second-largest supplier of wireless phones, Wednesday reported a
second-quarter operating profit that nearly doubled from the same
period last year amid stronger sales in broadband communications
and network systems.
</P>
<P>
Motorola said it earned 515 million U.S. dollars from ongoing
operations, or 23 cents per share in the quarter, excluding
special items, up 91 percent from 269 million dollars, or a split-
adjusted 13 cents a share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Second-quarter 2000 revenues climbed to 9.3 billion dollars
from 7.6 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In Motorola's widely watched personal communications segment,
which includes wireless phones, sales rose 20 percent to 3.3
billion dollars and orders declined less than 1 percent to 3.1
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in profitability in the second quarter versus
the first quarter was driven by better gross margins from phone
products and better overall conversion costs in manufacturing, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
In the network systems segment, sales increased 23 percent to 2.
0 billion dollars and orders were up 37 percent to 2.1 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Broadband communications unit sales increased 23 percent to 768
million dollars and orders increased 28 percent to 900 million
dollars from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In semiconductor products, sales increased 27 percent to 2.0
billion dollars and orders rose 31 percent to 2.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Overall company results continue to show solid improvement in
sales and profits," Robert L. Growney, Motorola's president and
chief operating officer, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"We are particularly pleased by the performance of the
Broadband Communications and Network Systems segments," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
