<HEADLINE> Thailand to Call for Reforms at G8 Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will appeal for reforms
in international trade and finance during Thursday's Group of
Eight (G8) ministerial meeting held in Miyazaki city, Japan, an
official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kobsak Chutikul, head of the Economic Affairs Department,
disclosed in a report that at the meeting Thai Foreign Minister
Surin Pitsuwan will ask the G8 to provide more technical
assistance for developing countries and to review past unbalanced
agreements.
</P>
<P>
G8 includes the United States, Canada, France, the United
Kingdom, Germany, Italy, Japan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Surin will also urge the International Monetary Fund to play a
more active role in macro economic management including early
warnings, surveillance and monitoring and ask it to regulate
capital flows of debtors and creditors, according to Kobsak.
</P>
<P>
Surin, together with representatives from South Africa,
Columbia, Bangladesh and Nigeria, was invited to attend the G8
ministerial meeting, which is held between July 12 and 13 in
Miyazaki, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and the mentioned four developing nations would ask
the G8 members to regularly consult them, Kobsak added.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai will meet G8 leaders in Tokyo
on July 20 before their summit in Okinawa, Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
