<HEADLINE> Joyner-Kersee Comes Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- World heptathlon record holder
Jackie Joyner-Kersee is coming out of retirement to compete in the
U.S. Olympic trials in the women's long jump, officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Games would be her fifth consecutive Olympics if 38-
year-old Joyner-Kersee makes the top three at the trials, which
begin Friday with long-jump qualifying.
</P>
<P>
Joyner-Kersee won Olympic gold medals in the heptathlon in 1988
and 1992 and in the long jump in 1988. She was a bronze medallist
in the 1996 Olympic long jump.
</P>
<P>
She set the heptathlon world record of 7,291 points at the 1988
Olympics and broke the U.S. record in the women's long jump with a
leap of 7.49 meters in 1994. 
