<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weakening Baht Helps Thailand's Recovery by Boosting Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The recent weakening of the Thai
baht will help support Thailand's economic recovery, given that
exports remained the country's main engine for growth, Bank of
Thailand's governor Chatumongol Sonakul was quoted Thursday by
Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the baht dipped as low as 40.16 to the U.S.
dollar, its weakest level for at least nine months. But
Chatumongol said the baht remained within "optimal" levels, and
said the central bank had no plans to intervene in the market.
</P>
<P>
"The baht has moved along with the currencies of our 22 main
trading partners, although some competitors, like the Philippines
and Indonesia, have seen greater weakness," he stated.
</P>
<P>
The baht's current value would boost Thailand's export
competitiveness, with exports remaining the only sector with
strong performance, as government spending and investment had
remained flat, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We see no necessity to intervene in the current situation,"
Chatumongol remarked.
</P>
<P>
He said even the baht dipping as low as 42 to the dollar and
oil prices of 30 dollars per barrel would remain acceptable.
</P>
<P>
"We have run economic models under that scenario and the
results came out that it is fairly acceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
He declined to say specifically at which point intervention
would be considered.
</P>
<P>
The weaker baht would have no impact on the country's debt
servicing ability, given existing current account surpluses and
foreign direct investment levels, according to him.
</P>
<P>
But some analysts said the economy remained fragile, given
recent revisions of total foreign debt upwards by 20 billion
dollars to 92 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The baht on Wednesday traded at 40.045/40.125 to the dollar,
gaining some ground after dropping as low as 40.165 before noon
and 39.955 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
Profit-taking by offshore players helped the baht's rebound in
the afternoon trading, dealers said, with short-term technical
targets now set at around 40.25/40.30 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Interbank rates have also shown increased volatility in the
past few days, with overnight rates quoted at 2.5-3 percent
Wednesday from 2 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said it was unlikely that the baht would break
41 to the dollar, and expected that the recent volatility will
ease in the next two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
With Thai export performance being still strong, fundamental
factors would support the baht against further declines, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
