<HEADLINE> U.S., Vietnam Ready to Sign Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Vietnam
are ready to sign a historic bilateral trade pact upon which they
have agreed in principle after closed-door negotiations over the
past week, trade sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There were only a few technical details to be hammered out and
a signing ceremony were expected in the next couple of days, said
the sources.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky and Vietnamese
Trade Minister Vu Khoan reportedly resolved the final outstanding
differences during their discussions Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky said Monday that both sides were "very close" to a
final agreement "but not yet".
</P>
<P>
The two sides resumed trade talks last Thursday in Washington
in a bid to strike a final trade pact.
</P>
<P>
If signed, the agreement would reduce tariffs on goods and
services, protect intellectual property and improve investment
relations between the two countries. 
</P>
