<HEADLINE> Indonesian Top Political Leaders' Scheduled Meeting Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The planned meeting of Indonesia's
four most influential political figures on Wednesday was delayed
for an indefinite period.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the cancellation of the meeting, President
Abdurrahman Wahid said that he and Vice President Megawati
Soekarnoputri, People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) Chairman Amien
Rais and House of Representatives (DPR) Speaker Akbar Tandjung
canceled the meeting due to different agendas and political
interests.
</P>
<P>
"It is very difficult for us to be together because each of us
has a different purpose, therefore I chose to stay here a little
bit longer," the president was quoted Thursday by the Indonesian
Observer as saying.
</P>
<P>
The president did not say if it would be rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
Wahid's close confidant and Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab said
the informal meeting was postponed after Rais opted out due to a
reported illness.
</P>
<P>
Akbar was originally named the host of Wednesday's event, the
follow-up to a previous meeting between Wahid, Akbar and Rais at
the Crown Plaza Hotel last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Observer speculated that the four top political
figures would meet soon in a bid to quell mounting political
bickering ahead of a key MPR session next month that has pummeled
the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah hit a 21-month low, closing at 9,415/9,425 per U.S.
dollar on Wednesday. The Indonesian currency has fallen 25 percent
so far this year on political and security concerns.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the benchmark one-month Bank Indonesia
certificates rate rose to 13.11 percent Wednesday from 12.69
percent last week. 
</P>
