<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Records 21 Percent Export Growth In 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka recorded a 21 percent
growth in exports during the first quarter of this year with
earnings up from 1.263 billion U.S. dollars to 1.533 billion
dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year, the
Daily News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Sri Lanka's Export Development Board (EDB)
G.L.J. Hewawasam Wednesday told the newspaper that the country's
export performance during the six-year period (1994-1999) has
reflected an annual average growth rate of 7.1 percent in dollar
terms.
</P>
<P>
The annual growth rate was significant during the initial years
of 1995 to 1997 which recorded a 18.23 percent growth in dollar
term. But from 1998 onwards due to the East Asian financial crisis,
the Russian Rouble crisis and other factors, Sri Lanka's export
growth rates have been lowered, Hewawasam said.
</P>
<P>
A market development scheme was adopted by the government for
the entire export sector with single country exhibitions, special
product trade fairs, multi-product exhibitions and sales missions
in both established and emerging markets in western countries like
Japan and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Significant achievements in the export sector is that between
1994 and 1999 textiles and garments increased from 1.55 billion
dollars in 1994 to 3.42 billion dollars in 1999 and industrial
exports went up from 2.47 billion dollars in 1994 to 3.51 billion
dollars in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
