<HEADLINE> Status quo Forces in Indonesia Exploit Press Freedom: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid has accused the forces loyal to former President Soeharto of
exploiting press freedom to fight against political reforms in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The status quo forces are fighting against political reform
through the media that they control, the Jakarta Post daily
Thursday quoted the president as saying.
</P>
<P>
But Wahid ruled out controlling the press the way Soeharto
often did.
</P>
<P>
"Parties defending the (Political) status quo are using every
means to prevent change. They do this by buying up shares and
taking control of media institutions," Wahid said Wednesday here
at a seminar on the ethics of journalism.
</P>
<P>
Although falling short of naming the parties or the media, he
said the media involved are distorting facts, concealing positive
achievements and giving undue attention to the negative aspects of
his administration. "They make it look like my administration is
about to fall apart," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that all the five commercial TV stations are owned
or partly owned by children and cronies of Soeharto. They also
control some newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
Wahid also criticized the press in general for their failure to
uphold the foremost principle in the journalist' code of ethics,
namely accuracy.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed the need for the media to adhere to
their code of ethics and conduct as they enjoy the freedom now
guaranteed by law. 
