<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottey Returns to Race after Doping Ban Lifted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Jamican sprinter Merleno Ottey won
the women's 100-meters in a regional track in Nuoro of Italy on
Wednesday, only nine days after being cleared of accusations that
she used steroids.
</P>
<P>
"It felt good to get started again," the 40-year-old five-time
Olympian said after the race."My goal now is to get to Sydney and
reach 20 years of Olympics."
</P>
<P>
Ottey, a double silver medalist at the 1996 Games, said the
doping ban that had kept her out of international competition for
12 months was ``like being sentenced to life in prison for
something you didn't do.''
</P>
<P>
Track and field's world governing body, the IAAF, reinstated
Ottey last Monday after concluding that a Swiss lab had improperly
tested her urine sample when she came up positive for the steroid
nandrolone at a meet in Switzerland in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
Her next competition will be the Jamaican national championship,
July 20-22 where she will run the 100 and 200 meters, seeking to
qualify for her sixth Olympic Games. Ottey has won 34 individual
medals in major international championships and is a former world
200-meter champion.
</P>
<P>
In its decision to reinstate the sprinter, the IAAF said its
arbitration panel found fault with the Swiss laboratory, saying it`
`had not taken into sufficient account factors regarding the
specific gravity of the sample which as a result did not exceed
the IOC (International Olympic Committee) recommended reporting
threshold.''
</P>
<P>
Nandrolone is a steroid that is easily detectable in standard
drug tests. However, there have been a spate of positive
nandrolone cases around the world over the past year, prompting
speculation that the drug is contained in nutritional supplements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
