<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (rpt with correction) U.S. Pays U.N. 135 Million U.S. Dollars, Still Owes Over 1.5 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
reduced its debt to the United Nations by some 135 million U.S.
dollars, but still owes more than 1.5 billion dollars, a U.N.
spokeswoman said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 135-million-dollar payment went to reduce arrears to a
number of U.N. peacekeeping operations, 30 percent of whose costs
are assessed against the United States according to the
universally accepted principle of "the capacity to pay."
</P>
<P>
But Washington still owes some 1.16 billion dollars for
peacekeeping and about 460 million in arrears to the regular
budget, for which the U.S. assessment is 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The United States is often under fire at the United Nations
for its reluctance to pay its back dues full, on time and without
conditions. However, Washington is seeking a review by the General
Assembly of the scale of assessment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
