<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NW China Builds Irrigation Project With WB Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Shaanxi Province, an arid area in
northwest China, is expected to turn 60,000 hectares of dry land
into irrigated fields when a World Bank-funded project is
completed.
</P>
<P>
The project involves an investment of 1.43 billion yuan (150
million U.S. dollars), including a 57.7 million U.S. dollars of
loan offered by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
At present, construction of three pump stations, a 130-km-long
canal and a 5-km-long tunnel is winding up. During a recent test
operation, 1,066 ha of land were watered.
</P>
<P>
When fully operational in October, the irrigation project is to
bring adequate water to 60,000 ha of dry land and provide clean
drinking water for 300,000 people. It will yield an estimated
added-value of 700 million yuan annually, said a local government
official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeological Survey Tells True Figures of Murals Plundered by Foreign Explorers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A recent archeological survey in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region showed that the
amount of murals plundered by foreign explorers at Kizil Thousand
Buddha Cave some 90 years ago was much more than the figure they
had announced before.
</P>
<P>
The One Thousand Buddha Cave, located in Baicheng County of
Aksu Prefecture, is the largest group of grottoes cut in the
ancient Guizi State of Western Regions with 236 caves. It is one
of the four famous grottoes in China together with grottoes at
Dunhuang in Gansu Province, Longmen in Henan Province and Yungang
in Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The German royal inspection team went to Kizil caves in 1906
and 1913 respectively and took many murals away. A report
published by Germany in 1933 say it had taken 252 pieces of murals
from 37 caves in Kizil with a total area of 328 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The one-year archeological survey proved that almost all the 60
caves found at that period were plundered by explorers from Russia,
Japan and Germany. A total of 480 square meters of murals were
taken away, most of which were stolen by the Germans.
</P>
<P>
Huo Xuchu, a researcher at the Guizi Grottoes Institute,
attributed the difference between the two figures to the amount of
murals damaged in the course of transportation to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Albert Grunwedel, head of the then German royal inspection team,
admitted that the Chinese murals are of great importance to the
study of the history of arts in central Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Once a complete set of murals is destroyed, it is impossible
for others to study the general picture of these murals," said
Huang Wenbi, a noted Chinese archeologist.
</P>
<P>
"Though the historical period that made us sad has elapsed, the
regret created by the history must be made up," Huo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0293 </DOCNO>
