<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,200-Year Old Mint Found in NW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists recently
found a mint site from the Han Dynasty (B.C.206-A.D.220) in the
western suburbs of this capital of Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The 900,000-square meter site, located in Huxian County, 20 km
from the city's downtown, is well preserved, said an archaeologist.
</P>
<P>
An abundance of historical relics related to ancient coin-
making were unearthed from the site, including coins of various
kinds as well as bronze molds, kilns, pottery stoves and iron
tools used in coin minting.
</P>
<P>
The site was most likely a national-level mint in the Han
Dynasty, the expert said, adding that the find will provide
valuable clues for the study of China's history of coin production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
