<HEADLINE> U.N. to Step Up Mideast Peace Efforts: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.N. Mideast Envoy Terje
Roed-Larsen said here Thursday that the U.N. will step up its
efforts to help achieve a peace in the region under the framework
of relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a press conference after a meeting with
Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah al-Khatib over the latest
developments in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The envoy stressed that the U.N. will mainly work under the
framework of all U.N. resolutions on the Middle East, and help
parties concerned to find solutions to their conflicts.
</P>
<P>
On Lebanon, Larsen said the U.N. has provided help to the
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, and the U.N. hoped the
ongoing sporadic conflicts on the Israel-Lebanon border would cease
by the end of July after the two sides reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Larsen arrived here earlier in the day for a brief visit as
part of his regional tour.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib and Larsen also reached an understanding of the issue
of Palestinian refugees in the kingdom, Jordan's official news
agency Petra reported without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has taken in 1.5 million Palestinian refugees, most of
whom have been granted Jordanian citizenships, but Jordan supports
their rights to choose between returning home or staying in the
kingdom while asking for compensations from parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Larsen left Amman for Israel Thursday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
