<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Anti-Drug Fund Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton Thursday
signed a bill aimed at helping step up the battle against the
Colombian drug trade.
</P>
<P>
A written statement with his comment will be issued later after
he privately signed the bill, approved late last month by the
House of Representatives and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The measure includes 1.3 billion dollars to help train and
equip Colombia's military and national police to wage war on drug
trafficking and rebels in the Andean nations, which produces much
of the cocaine and heroin on U.S. streets.
</P>
<P>
The funds will pay for 18 Black Hawk and 42 Huey helicopters to
ferry troops into coca-growing regions, training for officers
specializing in the war against drugs, intelligence operations and
human rights programs in the region.
</P>
<P>
The bill that Clinton signed also includes funds for the so-
called peace-keeping mission in Kosovo, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Early last year, the U.S.-led NATO force bombed Yugoslavia in
the name of protecting the Albanian minority in Kosovo. Later, the
NATO force entered Kosovo to discharge its "peace-keeping" mission
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
