<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian and Chilean
governments will examine the establishment of bioceanic corridors,
Chilean Foreign Minister Soledad Alvear said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bioceanic corridors would make up an eventual part of an accord
to be signed between the National Aeronautic Company of Chile (
Enaer) and Brazil's to Embraer, said the head of Chile's
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
Alvear is accompanying President Ricardo Lagos, who arrived in
Brazil Wednesday for a tree-day visit.
</P>
<P>
One of the corridors would connect the Chilean ports of Arica
and Ireque, the Peruvian port of Ilo, and Santos in Brazil and
would include Tambo Quemado and Santa Cruz de la Sierra stretches
in Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
Another corridor would lie between the Chilean port of
Antofagasta, and Resistencia and Santos in Brazil, and would
include Salta and Jujuy (Argentina).
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that though there's an aeronautic
accord, Enaer will make parts for tail ends of Brazilian military
and trade planes.
</P>
<P>
Lagos met this Thursday Brazilian President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso at the Planalto Palace, where both leaders signed a joint
statement. 
