<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Pledges to Change Laws to Meet WTO Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine has submitted a large
amount of documents at the working party on its accession to the
World Trade Organization (WTO) and pledged to bring its laws into
conformity with WTO rules, trade sources said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Economy Andriy Gonchurak made a statement in
which he described the new stage of economic reforms which began
after Kuchma was re-elected president in November 1999 and took
further shape in the "Reforms for Wellbeing" approved by the
Verkhovna Rada in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Privatization of large-scale industries, profound market
reform in the control over the economy, liberalization of markets
of trade in goods and services are among key components of the
program," Gonchurak said.
</P>
<P>
He listed statistics from the first five months of 2000 showing
how the Ukrainian economy is improving. He said, "For the first
time in the history of Ukraine's independence, a 5.4 percent
growth in GDP was reached."
</P>
<P>
He added that "the most dynamic growth of production activity
is observed in industrial sectors oriented at the domestic market
and producing end-products."
</P>
<P>
Growth rates in these sectors include 31.4 percent for the
textiles industry, 31.9 percent for foodstuffs production, and 37.
3 percent for wood processing and pulp and paper.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has almost finished market access negotiations with
some members, but not the major players such as the U.S. and EU,
and more informal meetings are possible towards the end of the
year, but not necessarily the working party. The previous meeting
was in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Trade sources believe that a lot of work remains on Ukraine's
accession negotiation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
