<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's June Inflation Up but Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada's annual inflation rate was
up to 2.9 percent in June from 2.4 percent in May, largely as a
result of soaring gasoline prices, Statistics Canada reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But the country's core inflation rate, which excludes energy
and food, remained steady at 1.4 percent, indicating that the Bank
of Canada is under no pressure to raise interest rates in the
short term and the Canadian dollar will remain stable.
</P>
<P>
"Core consumer prices remained well-behaved, with the year-over-
year rate of change staying below the Bank of Canada's one to
three percent target band," said Craig Alexander, a leading
economist of the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, at the
release of the inflation report by Statistics Canada.
</P>
<P>
Among major inflation contributors, gasoline prices rose 6.3
percent from May to June, accounting for nearly half of the rise
in the overall price index.
</P>
<P>
Mortgage interest rates rose 0.7 percent on a month-to-month
basis, the highest jump since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Hotels and Motels entered into summer rates by raising prices
by 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tuition fees, natural gas and fuel oil also cost more in June
while the effects were offset by flat or declining prices of autos,
clothing, fresh fruit, furniture and computers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
