<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Closes World AIDS Conference with Call for Greater Cooperation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela on Friday closed the 13th International
AIDS Conference in Durban by calling on the international
community to rise above differences and combine efforts to fight
the scourge.
</P>
<P>
"We have to rise above our differences and combine our efforts
to save our people. History will judge us harshly if we fail to do
so now, and right now, " said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He noted that these people, who were most afflicted by the HIV/
AIDS scourge, would want their needs addressed with collective
action.
</P>
<P>
Mandela received a resounding welcome from AIDS experts and
international media alike when he arrived at the conference, which
was attended by 2,700 delegates from 200 nations and regions.
</P>
<P>
The retired president said that the only way to stem the tide
of the HIV pandemic was to adopt a multi-sectoral approach, adding
large-scale actions were needed to prevent mother-to-child
transmission.
</P>
<P>
Mandela encouraged the search for a vaccine, which is estimated
to need five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized the need for information programs to spread
awareness of the disease.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge is to move from rhetoric to action, and action
at an unprecedented intensity and scale," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
The former president also rebuked those who criticized
President Thabo Mbeki or his support of "dissident" scientists who
challenged the traditional theory that HIV causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"The president of this country is a man of great intellect who
takes scientific thinking very seriously and leads a government
that I know to be committed to those principles of science and
reason," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said Mbeki had been instrumental in driving AIDS
initiatives when he was deputy president, and "continues to place
this issue on top of the national and continental agenda".
</P>
<P>
Mandela also committed his foundation to exploring ways in
which it could get involved in the battle to contain the scourge.
</P>
<P>
He said it was up to Africans to fight the disease ravaging its
people.
</P>
<P>
"Others will not save us if we do not primarily commit
ourselves," Mandela said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
