<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: World Awakened to Gravity of AIDS, but More Action Needed by Yu Dabo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The 13th International AIDS
Conference, with the theme of "breaking silence", ended in Durban,
South Africa on Friday after focusing world attention on the
gravity of the disease.
</P>
<P>
About 13,000 delegates from across the world reiterated their
commitment to curbing the pandemic, but frustration was also
shared by the delegates over the disproportionate spread of
resources to combat the disease.
</P>
<P>
The conference came to the conclusion that governments,
scientists, businesses and activists all play a part in driving
the AIDS pandemic to the forefront of the global agenda.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic has claimed 18.8 million lives since the first
AIDS patient was diagnosed in 1981. Now almost 35 million people
are suffering from the disease, with the majority in developing
countries, the sub-Saharan Africa in particular.
</P>
<P>
The dominant theme at the six-day conference had been the need
for poor countries, which bear the brunt of the pandemic, to have
access to expensive treatment that is only available to wealthy
countries.
</P>
<P>
It was revealed that 12 million AIDS sufferers in developing
countries would die in the next five years because of the
prohibitive cost of anti-retroviral drugs and the failing health
care infrastructures of the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that more than 90 percent of those who need HIV
drugs have no way of getting them, fueling the spread of the
pandemic.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, thousands of people living with the disease in the
industrialized world led relatively full and healthy lives because
they had access to medicine which suppressed the HIV and treated
opportunist infections.
</P>
<P>
But to buy anti-retroviral drugs at current prices for all
those who need them would cost 60 billion U.S. dollars a year,
making the anti-AIDS task too formidable for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Some delegates also associated the spread of AIDS with
worsening poverty in developing countries. They shared the view of
South African President Thabo Mbeki that the world's biggest
killer and greatest cause of ill-health and suffering was extreme
poverty, and not the HIV/AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
There had been a strong call for debt relief so as to allow
developing countries to have more resources to fight AIDS. African
debt servicing amounts to 15 billion dollars annually, and the
continent was in need of about 3 billion dollars every year for
basic AIDS prevention and treatment.
</P>
<P>
African delegates noted that without debt relief, African
countries would lack resources to fight the war over AIDS. The
conference, however, seemingly have failed to persuade developed
countries to come to African countries' recuse with debt relief.
</P>
<P>
International Monetary Fund managing director Horst Kohler said
during the conference that simply writing off Africa's debt was
not a wise option, as it may serve as a disincentive for Africans
to do something to improve their own situation.
</P>
<P>
This prompted African delegates to call for more reliance on
African efforts to seek a solution suitable for the African
continent through coordinated efforts. African scientists launched
the African Strategy for an HIV vaccine at the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference disclosed that two main strains of the virus
were found in Africa, and African scientists will focus on
developing a "broad" vaccine which could effectively deal with the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Also encouraging was the announcement by the South African
government that a new vaccine Nevirapine has been developed as a
cheaper alternative to AZT in reducing mother-to-child
transmissions. Research revealed that only two doses of Nevirapine,
at a cost of about four dollars, would significantly reduce the
number of babies who tested HIV positive after birth.
</P>
<P>
The much-expected conference also offered other encouraging
signs. The U.N. anti-AIDS agency, UNAIDS, has sought to bring down
the cost of drugs used in combinations from between 25,000 dollars
and 12,000 dollars a year, to below 1,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under mounting pressure, pharmaceutical companies have begun
announcing donations of medicine and money to help African
countries fight the devastating AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The International AIDS Vaccine Initiative (IAVI) released a
detailed working five-year agenda on Monday, vowing to make AIDS
vaccines available to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, the international Bill and Melinda Gates
Foundation pledged 50 million dollars over five years to help
South Africa strengthen its primary health care system. The number
of South African AIDS victims is estimated at 4.2 million, the
highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Pharmaceutical giant Merck and Co. also announced it would join
the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation in donating 100 million
dollars worth of medicine and money to help fight AIDS in Botswana,
where nearly 36 percent of adults are infected.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, meanwhile, announced it had set aside 500
million dollars for anti-AIDS programs in African countries.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission also announced it was beginning a new
initiative which will work to expand access to existing prevention
and treatment options.
</P>
<P>
These joint efforts were boosted when the U.S. pledged a budget
of over 200 million dollars for this year to stop the spread of
AIDS in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
The conference has seen the world mobilized to confront the
challenge of AIDS. But it's widely hoped that the best of the
gathering can be translated into policy and, the more important,
be put into action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
