<HEADLINE> Nigeria's House of Representatives Gives Red Card to IMF Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Lower chamber of Nigeria's top
legislature, the House of Representatives, has passed a motion,
barring the government from taking a 1 billion U. S. dollar loan
offered by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The government must make all the details of the conditions
going with the loan clear to the House first, Nigerian press
Friday quoted the House leaders as saying.
</P>
<P>
The House leaders said on Thursday before passing the motion
that the government's move regarding to the loan appeared ill-
advised, considering that Nigeria is currently owing its foreign
creditors about 30 billion dollars in debt.
</P>
<P>
They said in view of the ongoing efforts to secure debt
cancellation, it would be unwise to go into another commitment
that is likely to worsen the country's indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government earlier barred all of its agencies from
borrowing money without its acceding, but saying that the interest
of the IMF loan is "very favorable" therefore beneficial to the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
