<HEADLINE> Africa's First Batch of Trolleys Produced: Malawian Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Malawi's Plumbing and Engineering
Works Company (PEW), which usually manufactures buses, claimed it
has become the first firm on the African continent to manufacture
rail trolleys locally, a report reaching here said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Using locally available raw materials and a 460,000-U.S.-dollar
World Bank loan, the company has produced six so-called gang
trolleys with a franchise licence from Wickham Rail Cars of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Wickham Rail Cars contracted out the company to produce the
trolleys under a Malawi railway system's restructuring process.
</P>
<P>
The first company to buy the trolleys is the Central Africa
Railways (CEAR), a consortium of American and Mozambican rail
companies, which has just won a 20-year concession to run the
railway system in Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Under the World Bank agreement, Austin Chilembwe, chairman of
the PEW, said the company was prospecting for other clients in the
Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) and the Common Market
for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
"Our future lies in the export market in the Southern African
region," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vice President Justin Malewezi said the Malawian
government welcomes the deal the company has entered with the
World Bank since it brought about the badly needed direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
He congratulated the company on earning the trust and
confidence of Wickham Rail Cars.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from assimilating the technology for manufacturing of the
trolleys, there is potential for PEW to export to the region," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
