<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Line Closure Costs Mozambique 7.5 Million U.S. dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The closure of the flood-wrecked
Limpopo Railway Line, linking Zimbabwe to the Mozambican port of
Maputo, has so far cost the Mozambican publicly-owned ports and
railway companies some 7.5 million U.S. dollars, said reports
reaching here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Mozambican CFM Company said that with the
534-kilometer railway line paralyzed, the company sees the losses
running some 50,000 dollars per day, as the Zimbabwean exports
destined for Maputo have to be transferred to South African ports.
</P>
<P>
CFM has begun emergency rehabilitation on the worst affected
stretches at a cost of 7 million dollars and hopes that the line
will be operational by September, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Major work on the line is currently under way in Chokwe
district, located in south Mozambique along the Limpopo river,
where 14 kilometers of track was destroyed by the flooding of the
river caused by cyclones earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
