<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Malnutrition Rate Among Kenyan Children in Drought-hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Malnutrition rates among Kenyan
children under five years old are unacceptably high as a result of
drought which has been declared a national disaster in 19
districts throughout the country, the U.N.Children's Fund (UNICEF)
has said.
</P>
<P>
A press release from UNICEF reaching here Friday said a food
and nutrition survey in six districts carried out in June by the
agency and the Applied Nutrition Program, University of Nairobi,
attests to this fact.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered some worst-affected divisions in Turkana,
Marsabit and Moyale districts in northern Kenya, and Mandera,
Wajir and Garissa districts in northeastern Kenya. The data
collected included weight, height and mid-upper circumference.
</P>
<P>
Based on weight for height, the malnutrition rates were: 37.2
percent in Kerio Division of Turkana, 35.2 percent in Loyeingalani
Division of Marsabit, 32.6 percent in Griftu Division of Wajir, 29.
4 percent in Shimbri Division of Mandera and 27.2 percent in
Modoogashe Division of Garissa and 17.3 percent in Obbu Division
of Moyale.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF said the results of the nutrition survey are being used
to better target supplementary feeding activities in the affected
areas.
</P>
<P>
The agency is ready to distribute 484 tons of UNIMIX (a high-
protein food specially for children under five) to the affected
population in Kenya, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, UNICEF is continuing its field emergency support
activities in water and sanitation sector and directly supporting
the maintenance, rehabilitation or installation of over 50 water
supply points in Turkana, Wajir and Garissa.
</P>
<P>
Forty additional pumps are being dispatched to the affected
districts for installation in sites being drilled by the Kenya
Army and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
In order to continue to provide health and nutrition
interventions in the affected areas, UNICEF needs an additional 1
million U.S. dollars for vaccines, needles, syringes, vitamin A,
UNIMIX and cold chain equipment, the release added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
