<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Musicians Want End to CD Piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The music industry on Thursday
urged the European Union to get tougher with Internet piracy and
urged the world's CD consumers to stop cyber shoplifting.
</P>
<P>
The International Federation of the Phonographic Industry,which
represents the global recording industry, backs the high-level
star-studded campaign against Internet music sharing through
companies such as Napster Inc., whose service allows computer
users to make perfect copies of digital recordings over the net.
</P>
<P>
The federation warned that Internet pirates are the big new
threat to the business with at least 25 million illegal files
available and up to 1 billion downloaded each year.
</P>
<P>
French composer Jean Michel Jarre has gathered over 1,400
signatures from artists around Europe calling for stronger
protection.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was time to stop considering the work of
musicians as toothpaste. "Six hundred thousand people work in the
music industry in Europe alone," he added.
</P>
<P>
The International Federation of the Phonographic Industry
criticized that the existing European Union anti-piracy proposals
were too lax.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc, first proposed to update copyright rules in 1998 to take
into account digital revolution by allowing private copying over
the computer networks.
</P>
<P>
The proposals have been discussed at length in the European
Parliament and by the governments of the EU member states. If
approved in the Autumn, private copying would be allowed unless
individual governments outlaw it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
