<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Formalizes Request for Mercosur Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Chile formalized Thursday its
request for adhering to the Southern Common Market (Mercosur),
Brazil's Minister of Foreign Affairs Luis Felipe Lampreia
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chile could become one of the bloc's effective members in
coming December during a Mercosur summit in Florinapoles, Brazil,
through an additional protocol to the Asuncion Treaty, Lampreia
said before the banquet offered by President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso to his Chilean counterpart, Ricardo Lagos, who is visiting
here.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the two leaders decided Thursday
morning during talks to begin effective negotiations to make Chile
's adhering Mercosur a reality.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations will hinge around four points, Lampreia explained.
The first point is adhering to norms and rules already approved by
Mercosur. The second refers to the question of macroeconomic
convergence, which is the path of the bloc's economic union, said
the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Quickening and deepening of free trade between Chileans and the
bloc is the third point, whose objective is to get as quick as
possible a zero tax between Chile and Mercosur member countries,
and widen quotas and horizons, Lampreia explained.
</P>
<P>
The fourth point refers to the Common External Tax, considered
as the main obstacle for Chile's full entry to Mercosur, because
there are "notorious and sensible" differences between both sides
in this matter, according to Lampreia.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Chile is only an associate member, along with
Bolivia, of the Mercosur, which is composed by Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Let Data Deal With U.S. Stand As It Is </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Thursday
said that there was no need to amend the trans-Atlantic deal on
data protection though the European Parliament had raised concerns
about its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
The union's Internal Market Commissioner Frits Bolkestein felt
that the deal offered Europeans enough protection for personal
data transferred to the United States, according to European
Commission spokesman Jonathan Todd.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman quoted the commissioner as adding that he would
recommend that the commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc, give the deal its final go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
The governments of the 15 EU member states have already
approved the data protection deal, yet the European Parliament
last week rejected the deal in a non-binding resolution. The
legislators argued that key provisions need to be re-negotiated to
strengthen data privacy and protection.
</P>
<P>
Some European as well as American business people have opposed
the deal, saying that individual privacy rights were not strong
enough while Bolkestein said that he would re-negotiate only if
those rights were violated.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations on a data protection pact dated back to the
introduction of EU data privacy rules that had been passed in 1998
to give national regulators the right to stop information from
being sent to other countries that lack adequate data protection
laws.
</P>
<P>
The United States is one such country that does not have data
protection laws but relies on a self-regulatory system to ensure
data privacy.
</P>
<P>
The trans-Atlantic data protection deal was designed to
facilitate easier transfer of consumer data in the insurance,
financial services, tourism and aviation sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Mostly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended mostly
higher Thursday as investors expected strong corporate earnings in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 5.30 at 10,788.71,
continuing its four days of rally.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 75.27 at 4,174.
86. The index gained 143.17 points Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 2.92 at 1,495.84.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied after the Internet software company Ariba
reported narrower-than-expected losses in the second quarter and
said it will be profitable within a year. Ariba's report raised
hope that strong earnings in the second quarter will be in view
for other companies.
</P>
<P>
Ariba rose sharply. Applied Micro Circuits and PMC-Sierra were
also higher.
</P>
<P>
But Yahoo! fell on profit-taking. The Internet portal led the
market's advance Wednesday after the company report better-than-
expected earnings in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector also performed well today and J.P. Morgan
rose. But old economy stocks such as General Electric, Merck and
Bristol Myers Squibb fell.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.42 at 659.71 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 15.54 at 939.43. But the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 2.51 at 542.76.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners slightly on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 1,473 up, 1,443 down and 468 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.02 billion shares from 994.63
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
