<DOCNO> XIE20000713.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness Absence Should Not Wreck Trial: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Law experts on
Thursday said that the refusal of some witnesses to testify at the
Lockerbie trial should not wreck the court procedure.
</P>
<P>
They argued that the absence of witnesses listed to give
evidence on airport security around Malta's Luqa was a hindrance
to the prosecution but not an obstacle to wreck the trial.
</P>
<P>
Court proceedings were adjourned for one day on Wednesday after
an undisclosed number of witnesses had refused to travel to the
Scottish court on Dutch soil to testify.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that it was not clear how crucial the absence of
the Maltese witnesses to testify would finally be but that some
other avenues remained open to obtain the testimony on Luqa
airport security.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution alleges Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin
Khalifa Fahima placed a bomb in a suitcase which was then placed
on an Air Malta jet departing from Luqa on the morning of December
21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day the suitcase was transferred onto the New York-
bound Pan Am Flight 103 that was blown out of the sky over
Lockerbie, killing all 259 people on board and 11 others on the
ground in the Scottish town.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans went on trial on May 3 before the Scottish
court at Camp Zeist, a former U.S. air force base in central
Netherlands. They are charged with conspiracy of murder,and
breach of international aircraft safety laws.
</P>
<P>
Al-Megrahi and Fhimah both pleaded innocent to the charges
which carry a maximum life sentence in a Scottish jail.
</P>
<P>
One of the prosecution's principal witnesses is a Libyan
defector who allegedly saw one of the defendants introduce the
suitcase onto the Air Malta flight at Luqa.
</P>
<P>
The trial, that got underway after almost 12 years of
investigation and preparation, was adjourned several times for
both technical and witness reasons.
</P>
<P>
The court was last adjourned for 12 days to give the
prosecution extra time to examine the statements given by
witnesses lifted by the defense team just prior to the start of
the trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
